84032>>>>>>>/// @Name        SET_DATABASE_NAME
84032>>>>>>>/// @Description This command overrides the database set in the INT file
84032>>>>>>>/// under DATABASE_SPACE_NAME. Any opens or finds will use the database
84032>>>>>>>/// specified here. This can be used when the database is not stated in
84032>>>>>>>/// the INT file or if the database needs to be dynamically changed for
84032>>>>>>>/// a certain query. If the database is not specified with this command
84032>>>>>>>/// or in the INT file, then the default database for the server will be
84032>>>>>>>/// used. To set the database to be used for embedded SQL statements,
84032>>>>>>>/// use SQL_USE_DATABASE.
84032>>>>>>>///
84032>>>>>>>/// @Assumptions
84032>>>>>>>/// @Status      Public
84032>>>>>>>/// @Drivers     SQLFlex, MySQLFlex and PGFlex
84032>>>>>>>/// @VersionNote Last Revised: 2013-10-09 by Aaron Gulack
84032>>>>>>>/// @See                 GET_DATABASE_NAME SQL_USE_DATABASE
84032>>>>>>>/// @INTOPT              DATABASE_SPACE_NAME
84032>>>>>>>///
84032>>>>>>>/// @Syntax SET_DATABASE_NAME to {database}
84032>>>>>>>/// @Param database                     Name of the database
84032>>>>>>>///
84032>>>>>>>/// @Example
84032>>>>>>>/// Login "localhost" "user" "pas123" "sql_drv"
84032>>>>>>>/// SET_DATABASE_NAME to "TestDB"
84032>>>>>>>/// Open Customer
84032>>>>>>>
84032>>>>>>>//=============================================================================
84032>>>>>>>/// @Name        GET_DATABASE_NAME
84032>>>>>>>/// @Description This command is used to get the name of the database
84032>>>>>>>/// currently being used. The name of the database is returned into the
84032>>>>>>>/// specified string. Even though this command works either way, it is
84032>>>>>>>/// typically used when the INT file does not contain the DATABASE_SPACE_NAME.
84032>>>>>>>///
84032>>>>>>>/// @Assumptions
84032>>>>>>>/// @Status      Public
84032>>>>>>>/// @Drivers     SQLFlex, MySQLFlex and PgFlex
84032>>>>>>>/// @VersionNote Last Revised: 2013-10-01 by Aaron Gulack
84032>>>>>>>/// @See SET_DATABASE_NAME SQL_USE_DATABASE
84032>>>>>>>///
84032>>>>>>>/// @Syntax GET_DATABASE_NAME to {variable}
84032>>>>>>>/// @Param variable                     Variable to hold the database name
84032>>>>>>>///
84032>>>>>>>/// @Example
84032>>>>>>>/// GET_DATABASE_NAME to sDbName
84032>>>>>>>
84032>>>>>>>//=============================================================================
84032>>>>>>>/// @Name        GET_NAME_SPACE
84032>>>>>>>/// @Description This command returns the name space, or schema, being
84032>>>>>>>/// used with the current application.
84032>>>>>>>///
84032>>>>>>>/// @Assumptions
84032>>>>>>>/// @Status      Public
84032>>>>>>>/// @Drivers     PgFlex
84032>>>>>>>/// @VersionNote Last Revised: 2013-10-01 by Aaron Gulack
84032>>>>>>>/// @See                 SET_NAME_SPACE
84032>>>>>>>///
84032>>>>>>>/// @Syntax GET_NAME_SPACE to {variable}
84032>>>>>>>/// @Param variable                     Variable to hold the returned name space.
84032>>>>>>>///
84032>>>>>>>/// @Example
84032>>>>>>>/// GET_NAME_SPACE to sNameSpace
84032>>>>>>>
84032>>>>>>>//=============================================================================
84032>>>>>>>/// @Name        SET_NAME_SPACE
84032>>>>>>>/// @Description This command sets the name space, or schema, to be used
84032>>>>>>>/// for the application. In Postgres, schemas are objects where all the
84032>>>>>>>/// tables,views and indexes are stored. Separate schemas are used to
84032>>>>>>>/// specify relational data. Note that this command will override the
84032>>>>>>>/// NAME_SPACE value in the INT file.
84032>>>>>>>///
84032>>>>>>>/// @Assumptions
84032>>>>>>>/// @Status      Public
84032>>>>>>>/// @Drivers     PgFlex
84032>>>>>>>/// @VersionNote Last Revised: 2009-08-14 By Ian Smith
84032>>>>>>>/// @See                 GET_NAME_SPACE
84032>>>>>>>/// @INTOPT              NAME_SPACE
84032>>>>>>>///
84032>>>>>>>/// @Syntax SET_NAME_SPACE to {variable}
84032>>>>>>>/// @Param variable                     Name of the name space
84032>>>>>>>///
84032>>>>>>>/// @Example
84032>>>>>>>/// SET_NAME_SPACE to "public"
84032>>>>>>>
84032>>>>>>>//=============================================================================
84032>>>>>>>/// @Name        SQL_USE_DATABASE
84032>>>>>>>/// @Description This command is used to specify which database is used
84032>>>>>>>/// for SQL statements only. Any normal table queries or changes will
84032>>>>>>>/// still use the default database, this only effects SQL statements.
84032>>>>>>>/// If none is specified then the default database is used. This can
84032>>>>>>>/// be useful if a certain SQL statement needs to query data from a
84032>>>>>>>/// database not currently being used. Note that this only works if
84032>>>>>>>/// the table name is not fully qualified in the SQl statement, i.e.
84032>>>>>>>/// "TestDB.Customer".
84032>>>>>>>///
84032>>>>>>>/// @Assumptions
84032>>>>>>>/// @Status      Public
84032>>>>>>>/// @Drivers     SQLFlex MySQLFLex PgSQL
84032>>>>>>>/// @VersionNote Last Revised: 2013-10-07 by Aaron Gulack
84032>>>>>>>/// @See                 SET_DATABASE_NAME GET_DATABASE_NAME
84032>>>>>>>///
84032>>>>>>>/// @Syntax SQL_USE_DATABASE of {server} to {database}
84032>>>>>>>/// @Param server                       Name of the server (Postgre only)
84032>>>>>>>/// @Param database                     Name of the database
84032>>>>>>>///
84032>>>>>>>/// @Example
84032>>>>>>>/// SQL_USE_DATABASE "testDB"
84032>>>>>>>///
84032>>>>>>>/// SQL_SET_STMT to "SELECT * FROM CUSTOMER WHERE STATUS = 'Active' "
84032>>>>>>>/// SQL_PREPARE_STMT
84032>>>>>>>/// SQL_EXECUTE_STMT
84032>>>>>>>/// SQL_FETCH_NEXT_ROW into sID sFirstName sLastName
84032>>>>>>>/// If (Found) Begin
84032>>>>>>>///     Showln sFirstName
84032>>>>>>>///     Showln sLastName
84032>>>>>>>/// End
84032>>>>>>>/// SQL_CANCEL_QUERY_STMT
84032>>>>>>>
84032>>>>>>>//=============================================================================
84032>>>>>>>/// @Name        SET_CURRENT_SQL_SERVER
84032>>>>>>>/// @Description This command is used to set the server to be used when
84032>>>>>>>/// opening tables. It will override the SERVER_NAME token in the INT file.
84032>>>>>>>/// If the server is not specified in the INT file or with this command,
84032>>>>>>>/// then the server used during login will be used. This command is only
84032>>>>>>>/// needed when connecting to multiple SQL servers. To set the server to
84032>>>>>>>/// use for embedded SQL statements, use SET_CURRENT_SQL_SERVER_CONNECTION.
84032>>>>>>>///
84032>>>>>>>/// @Assumptions
84032>>>>>>>/// @Status      Public
84032>>>>>>>/// @Drivers     All
84032>>>>>>>/// @VersionNote Last Revised: 2013-10-09 by Aaron Gulack
84032>>>>>>>/// @See                 GET_CURRENT_SQL_SERVER  SET_CURRENT_SQL_SERVER_CONNECTION GET_CURRENT_SQL_SERVER_CONNECTION
84032>>>>>>>/// @INTOPT              SERVER_NAME
84032>>>>>>>///
84032>>>>>>>/// @Syntax SET_CURRENT_SQL_SERVER to {server}
84032>>>>>>>/// @Param server                       Name of the server
84032>>>>>>>///
84032>>>>>>>/// @Example
84032>>>>>>>/// SET_CURRENT_SQL_SERVER to "localhost"
84032>>>>>>>
84032>>>>>>>//IGS - removed. CURRENT_SERVER is a property of Validation_List_Mixin so this
84032>>>>>>>//               replace conflicts with the property SET message.
84032>>>>>>>//#Replace SET_CURRENT_SERVER SET_CURRENT_SQL_SERVER
84032>>>>>>>
84032>>>>>>>//=============================================================================
84032>>>>>>>/// @Name        GET_CURRENT_SQL_SERVER
84032>>>>>>>/// @Description This command returns the name of the server to be used
84032>>>>>>>/// for opening and querying tables.
84032>>>>>>>///
84032>>>>>>>/// @Assumptions
84032>>>>>>>/// @Status      Public
84032>>>>>>>/// @Drivers     All
84032>>>>>>>/// @VersionNote Last Revised: 2013-10-07 by Aaron Gulack
84032>>>>>>>/// @See SET_CURRENT_SQL_SERVER SET_CURRENT_SQL_SERVER_CONNECTION GET_CURRENT_SQL_SERVER_CONNECTION
84032>>>>>>>///
84032>>>>>>>/// @Syntax GET_CURRENT_SERVER to {variable}
84032>>>>>>>/// @Param variable                     Variable to hold the server name
84032>>>>>>>///
84032>>>>>>>/// @Example
84032>>>>>>>/// GET_CURRENT_SQL_SERVER to sServer
84032>>>>>>>
84032>>>>>>>//IGS - removed. CURRENT_SERVER is a property of Validation_List_Mixin so this
84032>>>>>>>//               replace conflicts with the property GET message.
84032>>>>>>>//#Replace GET_CURRENT_SERVER GET_CURRENT_SQL_SERVER
84032>>>>>>>
84032>>>>>>>//=============================================================================
84032>>>>>>>/// @Name        SET_CURRENT_SQL_SERVER_CONNECTION
84032>>>>>>>/// @Description This command is used to specify which server to use for
84032>>>>>>>/// embedded SQL statements. By default, the last logged in server will
84032>>>>>>>/// be used. Note that in addition to setting the server, this command
84032>>>>>>>/// also sets the driver to be used. This command is only needed when
84032>>>>>>>/// connecting to multiple servers. To set the server for opening tables,
84032>>>>>>>/// use SET_CURRENT_SQL_SERVER.
84032>>>>>>>///
84032>>>>>>>/// @Assumptions
84032>>>>>>>/// @Status      Public
84032>>>>>>>/// @Drivers     All
84032>>>>>>>/// @VersionNote Last Revised: 2013-10-09 by Aaron Gulack
84032>>>>>>>/// @See                 GET_CURRENT_SQL_SERVER_CONNECTION GET_CURRENT_SQL_SERVER SET_CURRENT_SQL_SERVER
84032>>>>>>>///
84032>>>>>>>/// @Syntax SET_CURRENT_SQL_SERVER_CONNECTION of {constant} to {server}
84032>>>>>>>/// @Param constant                     MYSQLFLEX, ORAFLEX, PGFLEX, or SQLFLEX
84032>>>>>>>/// @Param server               Name of the server
84032>>>>>>>///
84032>>>>>>>/// @Example
84032>>>>>>>/// SET_CURRENT_SQL_SERVER_CONNECTION of SQLFLEX to "(localdb)\v11.0"
84032>>>>>>>
84032>>>>>>>//=============================================================================
84032>>>>>>>/// @Name        GET_CURRENT_SQL_SERVER_CONNECTION
84032>>>>>>>/// @Description This command returns the server currently being used for
84032>>>>>>>/// embedded SQL statements.
84032>>>>>>>///
84032>>>>>>>/// @Assumptions
84032>>>>>>>/// @Status      Public
84032>>>>>>>/// @Drivers     All
84032>>>>>>>/// @VersionNote Last Revised: 2013-10-09 by Aaron Gulack
84032>>>>>>>/// @See                 SET_CURRENT_SQL_SERVER_CONNECTION GET_CURRENT_SQL_SERVER SET_CURRENT_SQL_SERVER
84032>>>>>>>///
84032>>>>>>>/// @Syntax GET_CURRENT_SQL_SERVER_CONNECTION of {constant} to {variable}
84032>>>>>>>/// @Param constant                     MYSQLFLEX, ORAFLEX, PGFLEX, or SQLFLEX
84032>>>>>>>/// @Param variable             Variable to hold the name of the server
84032>>>>>>>///
84032>>>>>>>/// @Example
84032>>>>>>>/// GET_CURRENT_SQL_SERVER_CONNECTION of SQLFLEX to sServer
84032>>>>>>>
84032>>>>>>>//=============================================================================
84032>>>>>>>/// @Name        LOGIN_SQLFLEX
84032>>>>>>>/// @Description This command allows the user to login with a specified
84032>>>>>>>/// hostname. The default hostname that is passed is the path of the
84032>>>>>>>/// executable. Passing a custom hostname can be very useful for tracking
84032>>>>>>>/// a specific user for different situations. For example, if a company
84032>>>>>>>/// is using a terminal server and a whole sales team logs in under the
84032>>>>>>>/// same username and hostname, locating a specific user could otherwise
84032>>>>>>>/// be difficult. With this command, each user can pass a custom hostname,
84032>>>>>>>/// easily distinguishing themselves from other users.
84032>>>>>>>///
84032>>>>>>>/// @Assumptions
84032>>>>>>>/// @Status      Public
84032>>>>>>>/// @Drivers     SQLFlex
84032>>>>>>>/// @VersionNote Last Revised: 2013-10-02 by Aaron Gulack
84032>>>>>>>/// @See
84032>>>>>>>///
84032>>>>>>>/// @Syntax LOGIN_SQLFLEX {server} {username} {password} {hostname}
84032>>>>>>>/// @Param server               Server to use for login
84032>>>>>>>/// @Param username     Username to use for login
84032>>>>>>>/// @Param password     Password to use for login
84032>>>>>>>/// @Param hostname     Hostname to use for login
84032>>>>>>>///
84032>>>>>>>/// @Example
84032>>>>>>>/// LOGIN_SQLFLEX "localhost" "guestUser" "pas123" "WIN-MM7PQS5CP6C"
84032>>>>>>>
84032>>>>>>>//=============================================================================
84032>>>>>>>/// @Name        SQL_CANCEL_QUERY_STMT
84032>>>>>>>/// @Description This command is used to close any open cursors related to
84032>>>>>>>/// an SQL_EXECUTE_STMT. This should be used once the SQL statement has
84032>>>>>>>/// been executed and all rows have been fetched.
84032>>>>>>>///
84032>>>>>>>/// @Assumptions
84032>>>>>>>/// @Status      Public
84032>>>>>>>/// @Drivers     All
84032>>>>>>>/// @VersionNote Last Revised: 2013-10-03 by Aaron Gulack
84032>>>>>>>/// @See                 SQL_SET_STMT SQL_EXECUTE_STMT SQL_FETCH_NEXT_ROW SQL_APPEND_STMT SQL_PREPARE_STMT
84032>>>>>>>///
84032>>>>>>>/// @Syntax SQL_CANCEL_QUERY_STMT [of {FileName}]
84032>>>>>>>/// @Param FileName             Name of the file (optional)
84032>>>>>>>///
84032>>>>>>>/// @Example
84032>>>>>>>/// SQL_SET_STMT to "SELECT * FROM CUSTOMER WHERE STATUS = 'Active' "
84032>>>>>>>/// SQL_PREPARE_STMT
84032>>>>>>>/// SQL_BINDCOLUMNS_STMT of Customer to DF_BIND_ALL_COLUMNS
84032>>>>>>>/// SQL_EXECUTE_STMT of Customer
84032>>>>>>>/// SQL_FETCH_NEXT_ROW of Customer
84032>>>>>>>/// If (Found) Begin
84032>>>>>>>///     Showln Customer.FirstName
84032>>>>>>>///     Showln Customer.LastName
84032>>>>>>>/// End
84032>>>>>>>/// SQL_CANCEL_QUERY_STMT of Customer
84032>>>>>>>
84032>>>>>>>//=============================================================================
84032>>>>>>>/// @Name        NATIVE_OPTIMIZATION
84032>>>>>>>/// @Description Allows user to turn off the use of index hints on the native
84032>>>>>>>/// server. Setting this command to DEFAULT will cause the server to use the
84032>>>>>>>/// default settings for hints. Hints are off by default in Microsoft SQL
84032>>>>>>>/// Server but are on in Oracle. Care should be taken with changing the
84032>>>>>>>/// default, and should only be used if the diagnostics tool for your server
84032>>>>>>>/// indicates performance problems with the type of queries that are being
84032>>>>>>>/// generated. Note that this can be turned off or on for the whole server
84032>>>>>>>/// or just for a specific table.
84032>>>>>>>///
84032>>>>>>>/// DEFAULT             - The specified server's default settings
84032>>>>>>>/// USE_INDEXHINT       - All Index hints will be used
84032>>>>>>>/// NO_INDEXHINT        - No index hints will be used
84032>>>>>>>///
84032>>>>>>>/// @Assumptions
84032>>>>>>>/// @Status      Public
84032>>>>>>>/// @Drivers     SQLFlex, ORAFlex
84032>>>>>>>/// @VersionNote Last Revised: 2013-10-08 by Aaron Gulack
84032>>>>>>>/// @See
84032>>>>>>>///
84032>>>>>>>/// @Syntax NATIVE_OPTIMIZATION of {scopeLevel} {variable} to {constant}
84032>>>>>>>/// @Param scopeLevel           TABLE or SERVER. Indicates the scope of the setting
84032>>>>>>>/// @Param variable                     Either the name of the server or of the table
84032>>>>>>>/// @Param constant                     DEFAULT, USE_INDEXHINT, or NO_INDEXHINT
84032>>>>>>>///
84032>>>>>>>/// @Example
84032>>>>>>>/// NATIVE_OPTIMIZATION of SERVER "localhost" to USE_INDEXHINT
84032>>>>>>>
84032>>>>>>>//=============================================================================
84032>>>>>>>/// @Name        SET_ISOLATION_LEVEL
84032>>>>>>>/// @Description This command sets the locking and row versioning behavior
84032>>>>>>>/// for SQL statements. See the options below for information on the various
84032>>>>>>>/// effects they can have on transactions.
84032>>>>>>>///
84032>>>>>>>/// DEFAULT  - The default isolation level for the server (READ_COMMITTED
84032>>>>>>>/// for MSSQL).
84032>>>>>>>///
84032>>>>>>>/// READ_COMMITTED - This option is used to prevent dirty reads. A dirty
84032>>>>>>>/// read is when one transaction reads data from another transaction that
84032>>>>>>>/// has yet to be committed. If one transaction fails, the other now is
84032>>>>>>>/// dealing with invalid data. By setting the isolation level to
84032>>>>>>>/// READ_COMMITTED, dirty reads will be avoided by not allowing transactions
84032>>>>>>>/// to deal with any other data that has not been committed yet. However,
84032>>>>>>>/// in between statements within the current transaction, data can be changed
84032>>>>>>>/// by other transactions. This can result in phantom data or non-repeatable
84032>>>>>>>/// reads. Note that this can slow down performance speeds but is usually
84032>>>>>>>/// good practice.
84032>>>>>>>///
84032>>>>>>>/// READ_UNCOMMITTED - This option is the least restrictive isolation level.
84032>>>>>>>/// With this option, dirty reads are allowed, thus no exclusive locks are
84032>>>>>>>/// honored and modified data from one uncommitted transaction can be read
84032>>>>>>>/// by other transactions.
84032>>>>>>>///
84032>>>>>>>/// REPEATABLE_READ - This option is similar to the READ_COMMITTED option
84032>>>>>>>/// in that locks all placed on all transactions and uncommitted data from
84032>>>>>>>///     other transactions cannot be read, preventing dirty reads. However, unlike
84032>>>>>>>/// READ_COMMITTED, new rows that are added by other transactions can be read
84032>>>>>>>/// by the current transaction if it is retried, possibly resulting in phantom
84032>>>>>>>/// reads. This option should not be used unless there is a specific reason to
84032>>>>>>>/// do so.
84032>>>>>>>///
84032>>>>>>>/// SERIALIZABLE - This option is the most restrictive isolation level. With
84032>>>>>>>/// this option, no interaction is allowed between transactions until they
84032>>>>>>>/// have been committed. Similar to READ_COMMITTED, no transaction can deal
84032>>>>>>>/// with any uncommitted data. On top of that though, range locks are placed on
84032>>>>>>>/// all rows being modified until the current transaction is complete. Because
84032>>>>>>>/// concurrency is so low with this option, performance speeds can be much lower
84032>>>>>>>/// and so this should only be used when there is a specific reason to do so.
84032>>>>>>>///
84032>>>>>>>/// @Assumptions
84032>>>>>>>/// @Status      Public
84032>>>>>>>/// @Drivers     All
84032>>>>>>>/// @VersionNote Last Revised: 2013-10-08 by Aaron Gulack
84032>>>>>>>/// @See
84032>>>>>>>///
84032>>>>>>>/// @Syntax SET_ISOLATION_LEVEL of {server} to {constant}
84032>>>>>>>/// @Param server                       Name of the server
84032>>>>>>>/// @Param constant                     DEFAULT, READ_COMMITTED, READ_UNCOMMITTED, REPEATABLE_READ, or SERIALIZABLE
84032>>>>>>>///
84032>>>>>>>/// @Example
84032>>>>>>>/// LOGIN "localhost" "user" "pass123" "SQL_DRV"
84032>>>>>>>/// SET_ISOLATION_LEVEL of "localhost" to READ_COMMITTED
84032>>>>>>>
84032>>>>>>>//=============================================================================
84032>>>>>>>/// @Name        SET_SESSION_PARAMETER
84032>>>>>>>/// @Description There are two sets of code pages used in windows, ANSI and
84032>>>>>>>/// OEM. ANSI is what is commonly used now, but some data still uses the OEM
84032>>>>>>>/// code pages. When migrating data, this command is used to determine whether
84032>>>>>>>/// the OEM data will be translated to ANSI during the migration. For example,
84032>>>>>>>/// migrating passwords with special characters may call for different code
84032>>>>>>>/// pages. Sending true will convert the OEM data to ANSI, sending false will
84032>>>>>>>/// not. Both OEM_TO_ANSI and OEM_TRANSLATION_STATE do essentially the same
84032>>>>>>>/// thing, however since MSSQL has the functionality built in, OEM_TO_ANSI
84032>>>>>>>/// will use MSSQL's built in translation and thus only works with SQLFlex.
84032>>>>>>>/// OEM_TRANSLATION_STATE is internal and built into the driver so it works
84032>>>>>>>/// for all drivers. Note that if using custom entries with
84032>>>>>>>/// SET_CUSTOM_OEM_TO_ANSI then OEM_TRANSLATION_STATE must be used. Also, if
84032>>>>>>>/// there are already custom entries set then turning OEM_TRANSLATION_STATE
84032>>>>>>>/// on will automatically enable those custom translations.
84032>>>>>>>///
84032>>>>>>>/// @Assumptions
84032>>>>>>>/// @Status      Public
84032>>>>>>>/// @Drivers     All
84032>>>>>>>/// @VersionNote Last Revised: 2013-10-08 by Aaron Gulack
84032>>>>>>>/// @See                 SET_CUSTOM_OEM_TO_ANSI GET_CUSTOM_OEM_TO_ANSI
84032>>>>>>>///
84032>>>>>>>/// @Syntax SET_SESSION_PARAMETER {OEM_TO_ANSI/OEM_TRANSLATION_STATE} to {variable}
84032>>>>>>>/// @Param variable                     Boolean variable enabling or disabling translation
84032>>>>>>>///
84032>>>>>>>/// @Example
84032>>>>>>>/// SET_SESSION_PARAMETER OEM_TO_ANSI to True
84032>>>>>>>
84032>>>>>>>Procedure MertechInc_SET_CUSTOM_OEM_TO_ANSI Global Integer iChar Integer iOem Integer iAnsi
84034>>>>>>>    Move iChar to MertechInc_sArg1
84035>>>>>>>    move (String(iOem) + "," + String(iAnsi)) to MertechInc_sArg2
84036>>>>>>>    Call_Driver 0 MertechInc_DriverName Function CALLDRV_LICENSE_ENVIRONMENT_SET CALLBACK 0 PASSING MertechInc_sArg1 MertechInc_sArg2 CALLDRV_SET_CUSTOM_OEM_TO_ANSI RESULT MertechInc_iRet
84041>>>>>>>    IF MertechInc_iRet EQ -1 INDICATE ERR TRUE
84044>>>>>>>End_Procedure
84045>>>>>>>
84045>>>>>>>//=============================================================================
84045>>>>>>>/// @Name        SET_CUSTOM_OEM_TO_ANSI
84045>>>>>>>/// @Description In very rare situations, a custom OEM to ANSI translation
84045>>>>>>>/// is needed. When that is the case, this command can be used to create
84045>>>>>>>/// those custom entries. This is done by passing the character numbered
84045>>>>>>>/// position, the OEM value and the ANSI value. Note that
84045>>>>>>>/// OEM_TRANSLATION_STATE must be set to true for these custom entries to
84045>>>>>>>/// work.
84045>>>>>>>///
84045>>>>>>>/// @Assumptions
84045>>>>>>>/// @Status      Public
84045>>>>>>>/// @Drivers     All
84045>>>>>>>/// @VersionNote Last Revised: 2013-10-08 by Aaron Gulack
84045>>>>>>>/// @See                 GET_CUSTOM_OEM_TO_ANSI SET_SESSION_PARAMETER
84045>>>>>>>///
84045>>>>>>>/// @Syntax SET_CUSTOM_OEM_TO_ANSI {character} to OEM {value1} ANSI {value2}
84045>>>>>>>/// @Param character            Numbered position (0-255) of the character
84045>>>>>>>/// @Param value1                       Character number for the OEM value
84045>>>>>>>/// @Param value2                       Character number for the ANSI value
84045>>>>>>>
84045>>>>>>>Procedure MertechInc_GET_CUSTOM_OEM_TO_ANSI Global Integer iChar Integer iOem Integer iAnsi
84047>>>>>>>    Move iChar to MertechInc_sArg1
84048>>>>>>>    Move (Repeat(" ", 255)) to MertechInc_sArg2
84049>>>>>>>    Call_Driver 0 MertechInc_DriverName Function CALLDRV_LICENSE_ENVIRONMENT_SET CALLBACK 0 PASSING MertechInc_sArg1 MertechInc_sArg2 CALLDRV_GET_CUSTOM_OEM_TO_ANSI RESULT MertechInc_iRet
84054>>>>>>>    IF MertechInc_iRet EQ -1 INDICATE ERR TRUE
84057>>>>>>>End_Function
84058>>>>>>>
84058>>>>>>>//=============================================================================
84058>>>>>>>/// @Name        GET_CUSTOM_OEM_TO_ANSI
84058>>>>>>>/// @Description This command returns the custom OEM and ANSI values
84058>>>>>>>/// respectively for a given character. If there is no custom translation
84058>>>>>>>/// for the specified character then no error will be raised, but nothing
84058>>>>>>>/// will be returned.
84058>>>>>>>///
84058>>>>>>>/// @Assumptions There exists a custom translation for the specified character
84058>>>>>>>/// @Status      Public
84058>>>>>>>/// @Drivers     All
84058>>>>>>>/// @VersionNote Last Revised: 2013-10-08 by Aaron Gulack
84058>>>>>>>/// @See
84058>>>>>>>///
84058>>>>>>>/// @Syntax SET_CUSTOM_OEM_TO_ANSI {character} to OEM {value1} ANSI {value2}
84058>>>>>>>/// @Param character            Numbered position (0-255) of the character
84058>>>>>>>/// @Param value1                       Variable to hold the OEM value
84058>>>>>>>/// @Param value2                       Variable to hold the ANSI value
84058>>>>>>>
84058>>>>>>>//=============================================================================
84058>>>>>>>/// @Name        SET_AUTOMATIC_NUMERIC_DATATYPE_REMAPPING
84058>>>>>>>/// @Description This command toggles off and on the automatic numeric
84058>>>>>>>/// data type remapping built into SQLFlex. When adding or creating
84058>>>>>>>/// smaller numeric columns during a restructure, SQLFlex will change
84058>>>>>>>/// the type to a more specific data type i.e. smallint or tinyint since
84058>>>>>>>/// they are handled more efficiently by the server. Sending false to this
84058>>>>>>>/// command will force SQl to keep the column as a numeric field, preserving
84058>>>>>>>/// the length and precision. Passing true will leave the remapping up to the
84058>>>>>>>/// driver.
84058>>>>>>>///
84058>>>>>>>/// @Assumptions
84058>>>>>>>/// @Status      Public
84058>>>>>>>/// @Drivers     SQLFlex
84058>>>>>>>/// @VersionNote Last Revised: 2013-10-04 by Aaron Gulack
84058>>>>>>>/// @See
84058>>>>>>>///
84058>>>>>>>/// @Syntax SET_AUTOMATIC_NUMERIC_DATATYPE_REMAPPING to {variable}
84058>>>>>>>/// @Param variable                     Boolean variable enabling or disabling remapping
84058>>>>>>>///
84058>>>>>>>/// @Example
84058>>>>>>>/// Structure_Start hFile
84058>>>>>>>///
84058>>>>>>>///     Create_Field hFile
84058>>>>>>>///
84058>>>>>>>///     SET_AUTOMATIC_NUMERIC_DATATYPE_REMAPPING to False
84058>>>>>>>///
84058>>>>>>>///     Set_Attribute DF_FIELD_NAME   of hFile iColumn to "Transaction_Count"
84058>>>>>>>///     Set_Attribute DF_FIELD_TYPE   of hFile iColumn to DF_BCD
84058>>>>>>>///     Set_Attribute DF_FIELD_LENGTH of hFile iColumn to 1
84058>>>>>>>///
84058>>>>>>>/// Structure_End hFile
84058>>>>>>>
84058>>>>>>>//=============================================================================
84058>>>>>>>/// @Name        SET_FORCE_DATE_FORMAT_INIT
84058>>>>>>>/// @Description At times, a stored procedure, function or trigger may
84058>>>>>>>/// alter the default format for dates. This could cause problems because,
84058>>>>>>>/// for example, if a trigger on a table does this, then every time a save
84058>>>>>>>/// takes place on that table, the format for dates will be changed. By
84058>>>>>>>/// sending true to this command, the date formats will reset to their
84058>>>>>>>/// default format. Note that this is essentially the same thing as running
84058>>>>>>>/// the SQL statement: "ALTER SESSION SET NLS_DATE_FORMAT='MM/DD/YYYY'", so
84058>>>>>>>/// in most situations, that should be used instead of this command.
