84076>>>>>>>//=============================================================================
84076>>>>>>>/// @Name        COPY_DATA
84076>>>>>>>/// @Description This command is used to copy data from a DAT file to an
84076>>>>>>>/// SQL table. Both the source and the destination files are opened, the
84076>>>>>>>/// data is copied and then the files are closed. This is usually used
84076>>>>>>>/// along with CREATE_TABLE_FROM_DAT_FILE, which creates the structure
84076>>>>>>>/// and then this command will insert the data. If needed, this command
84076>>>>>>>/// can also work backwards, copying data from an SQL table to a DAT file.
84076>>>>>>>/// This is an alternative to using the Flex2SQL Migration Tool and can
84076>>>>>>>/// improve performance when used in the right situations. Note that in
84076>>>>>>>/// order for this process to work properly the table being copied can not
84076>>>>>>>/// be opened. Because of this, a manual login must take place, using
84076>>>>>>>/// something like LOGIN_SQLFLEX or LOGIN. Since this only copies the data,
84076>>>>>>>/// CREATE_TABLE_FROM_DAT_FILE can be used to create the table structure.
84076>>>>>>>///
84076>>>>>>>/// Because COPY_DATA requires no user interaction, an optional callback
84076>>>>>>>/// function can be passed for tracing purposes. By passing the constant
84076>>>>>>>/// "CALLBACK" followed by the object name, a function can be used to set
84076>>>>>>>/// up messages for tracking and error handling. Below is more information
84076>>>>>>>/// regarding this callback object.
84076>>>>>>>///
84076>>>>>>>/// This function should follow this pattern:
84076>>>>>>>///
84076>>>>>>>/// Function Callback String sText Integer iStatusID Returns Integer
84076>>>>>>>///
84076>>>>>>>/// sText - Message corresponding to the current status ID
84076>>>>>>>///
84076>>>>>>>/// iStatusID - Integer value mapping to the current status constant:
84076>>>>>>>///                     DF_MESSAGE_PROGRESS_TITLE    Sent when SQLFlex starts the
84076>>>>>>>///                                                                              process
84076>>>>>>>///
84076>>>>>>>///             DF_MESSAGE_HEADING_1         Sent when SQLFlex is about to
84076>>>>>>>///                                                                              copy the source data
84076>>>>>>>///
84076>>>>>>>///             DF_MESSAGE_ERROR             Sent when an error occurs
84076>>>>>>>///
84076>>>>>>>///             DF_MESSAGE_PROGRESS_STATUS   Sent each time an additional
84076>>>>>>>///                                                                              10% of the data is copied
84076>>>>>>>///
84076>>>>>>>/// NOTE: Returning false each time the function is called will continue
84076>>>>>>>/// copying process. Returning true will end it.
84076>>>>>>>///
84076>>>>>>>/// Another optional parameter that can be used is a constrain on the data
84076>>>>>>>/// being copied. This is done by passing the constant "CONSTRAIN" followed
84076>>>>>>>/// by an SQL constrain statement. When passing a constrain but not a callback
84076>>>>>>>/// object, pass 0 for the callback before passsing the constrain.
84076>>>>>>>///
84076>>>>>>>/// @Assumptions
84076>>>>>>>/// @Status      Public
84076>>>>>>>/// @Drivers     All
84076>>>>>>>/// @VersionNote Last Revised: 2013-10-08 by Aaron Gulack
84076>>>>>>>/// @See                 CREATE_TABLE_FROM_DAT_FILE CONVERT_DAT_FILE
84076>>>>>>>///
84076>>>>>>>/// @Syntax COPY_DATA {from} to {destination} [CALLBACK {function}] [CONSTRAIN {variable}]
84076>>>>>>>/// @Param from                         Table to copy from.
84076>>>>>>>/// @Param destination          Table to copy to.
84076>>>>>>>/// @Param function             Object with callback function (optional)
84076>>>>>>>/// @Param variable                     SQL contraint to use when copying (optional)
84076>>>>>>>///
84076>>>>>>>/// @Example
84076>>>>>>>/// Object CallBackObj is a Array
84076>>>>>>>///     Function Callback String sText Integer iLogicalID Returns Integer
84076>>>>>>>///         If (iLogicalID = DF_MESSAGE_ERROR) Begin
84076>>>>>>>///             Showln "Error"
84076>>>>>>>///                             Showln sText
84076>>>>>>>///                             Function_Return True
84076>>>>>>>///         End
84076>>>>>>>///
84076>>>>>>>///         Else Showln sText
84076>>>>>>>///
84076>>>>>>>///                     Function_Return False
84076>>>>>>>///
84076>>>>>>>///     End_Function
84076>>>>>>>/// End_Object
84076>>>>>>>///
84076>>>>>>>/// Login "localhost" "user" "pass123" "sql_drv"
84076>>>>>>>/// CREATE_TABLE_FROM_DAT_FILE Customer.File_Number "Customer"
84076>>>>>>>/// COPY_DATA "Customer" to "sql_drv:Customer" CALLBACK (Callback(Self)) CONSTRAIN "STATUS = 'Active'"
84076>>>>>>>
84076>>>>>>>//=============================================================================
84076>>>>>>>/// @Name        ORAFlex_REVISION
84076>>>>>>>/// @Description This command will put the current version (decimals included)
84076>>>>>>>/// of the Oracle driver associated with the current workspace into the specified
84076>>>>>>>/// variable.
84076>>>>>>>///
84076>>>>>>>/// @Assumptions
84076>>>>>>>/// @Status      Deprecated
84076>>>>>>>/// @Drivers     ORAFlex
84076>>>>>>>/// @VersionNote Last Revised: 2013-10-01 by Aaron Gulack
84076>>>>>>>/// @See                 GET_DRIVER_REVISION
84076>>>>>>>///
84076>>>>>>>/// @Syntax ORAFlex_REVISION {variable}
84076>>>>>>>/// @Param variable                     String variable to hold the returned version
84076>>>>>>>///
84076>>>>>>>/// @Example
84076>>>>>>>/// ORAFlex_REVISION sVersion
84076>>>>>>>
84076>>>>>>>//=============================================================================
84076>>>>>>>/// @Name        KEEP_FILES_OPEN
84076>>>>>>>/// @Description Keep the files, currently in use, open after the server is
84076>>>>>>>/// logged out. Sometimes an application needs to login to the same server
84076>>>>>>>/// with a different user id. When logging out, however, the drivers
84076>>>>>>>/// automatically close all opened files. The overhead of opening these files
84076>>>>>>>/// should be avoided if the user will work with the same files that were
84076>>>>>>>/// closed. KEEP_FILES_OPEN keeps all files opened after a user logs out
84076>>>>>>>/// from the server.
84076>>>>>>>///
84076>>>>>>>/// @Status      Deprecated
84076>>>>>>>/// @Drivers     All
84076>>>>>>>/// @VersionNote Last Revised: 2013-10-02 by Aaron Gulack
84076>>>>>>>///
84076>>>>>>>/// @Syntax KEEP_FILES_OPEN of {server}
84076>>>>>>>/// @Param server               Name of the server
84076>>>>>>>
84076>>>>>>>
84076>>>>>>>//=============================================================================
84076>>>>>>>/// @Name        SET_MAX_OPEN_CURSORS
84076>>>>>>>/// @Description Set the maximum number of cursors you want the driver to use.
84076>>>>>>>///
84076>>>>>>>/// The driver will recycle the least used cursors if this limit is hit.
84076>>>>>>>/// The trade off is between increased resources on the server and
84076>>>>>>>/// re-preparing of cursors.
84076>>>>>>>///
84076>>>>>>>/// For a program that keeps 40+ files opened at the same time, 255 is a good
84076>>>>>>>/// number for the open cursors parameter. For programs that open less than
84076>>>>>>>/// 40 files, any number between 100-255 is sufficient. These numbers can be
84076>>>>>>>/// changed based on available server resources.
84076>>>>>>>///
84076>>>>>>>/// On Oracle this value should not exceed the value of open_cursors in
84076>>>>>>>/// init.ora
84076>>>>>>>///
84076>>>>>>>/// Note: Only change this setting if you are having performance issues
84076>>>>>>>/// and the server is indicating you are using up too many cursors or too
84076>>>>>>>/// much memory. GET_OPENED_CURSORS can be used to check the number of
84076>>>>>>>/// cursors the server has opened. If this number is hitting the limit,
84076>>>>>>>/// it is worth increasing the number, as long as the server has enough
84076>>>>>>>/// resources.
84076>>>>>>>///
84076>>>>>>>/// @Assumptions
84076>>>>>>>/// @Status      Public
84076>>>>>>>/// @Drivers     All
84076>>>>>>>/// @VersionNote Last Revised: 2013-10-04 by Aaron Gulack
84076>>>>>>>/// @See         GET_MAX_OPEN_CURSORS GET_OPENED_CURSORS
84076>>>>>>>///
84076>>>>>>>/// @Syntax SET_MAX_OPEN_CURSORS of {server} to {variable}
84076>>>>>>>/// @Param server                       The name of the server
84076>>>>>>>/// @Param variable                     Maximum number of cursors
84076>>>>>>>
84076>>>>>>>//=============================================================================
84076>>>>>>>/// @Name        GET_MAX_OPEN_CURSORS
84076>>>>>>>/// @Description This command will return the maximum number of open
84076>>>>>>>/// cursors allowed by the server.
84076>>>>>>>///
84076>>>>>>>/// @Assumptions
84076>>>>>>>/// @Status      Public
84076>>>>>>>/// @Drivers     All
84076>>>>>>>/// @VersionNote Last Revised: 2013-10-04 by Aaron Gulack
84076>>>>>>>/// @See         SET_MAX_OPEN_CURSORS GET_OPENED_CURSORS
84076>>>>>>>///
84076>>>>>>>/// @Syntax GET_MAX_OPEN_CURSORS of {server} to {variable}
84076>>>>>>>/// @Param server                       Name of the server
84076>>>>>>>/// @Param variable                     Variable to hold the maximum number of open cursors
84076>>>>>>>
84076>>>>>>>//=============================================================================
84076>>>>>>>/// @Name        GET_OPENED_CURSORS
84076>>>>>>>/// @Description This command returns the number of cursors currently
84076>>>>>>>/// open on the server.
84076>>>>>>>///
84076>>>>>>>/// @Assumptions
84076>>>>>>>/// @Status      Public
84076>>>>>>>/// @Drivers     All
84076>>>>>>>/// @VersionNote Last Revised: 2013-10-04 by Aaron Gulack
84076>>>>>>>/// @See         SET_MAX_OPEN_CURSORS GET_MAX_OPEN_CURSORS
84076>>>>>>>///
84076>>>>>>>/// @Syntax GET_MAX_OPEN_CURSORS of {server} to {variable}
84076>>>>>>>/// @Param server                       Name of the server
84076>>>>>>>/// @Param variable                     Variable to hold the number of cursors currently open
84076>>>>>>>///
84076>>>>>>>
84076>>>>>>>//=============================================================================
84076>>>>>>>/// @Name        ACTIVATE_TIME_STAMP
84076>>>>>>>/// @Description This command will specify whether or not to show the time
84076>>>>>>>/// portion of a date field. When set to ON, the time portion will be
84076>>>>>>>/// included, OFF will just show the date. This is the same as changing
84076>>>>>>>/// the date format with "ALTER SESSION SET nls_timestamp_format". Note that
84076>>>>>>>/// this will only take effect if the date is put into a string variable.
84076>>>>>>>///
84076>>>>>>>/// @Assumptions
84076>>>>>>>/// @Status      Deprecated
84076>>>>>>>/// @Drivers     OraFlex
84076>>>>>>>/// @VersionNote Last Revised: 2013-10-09 by Aaron Gulack
84076>>>>>>>/// @See
84076>>>>>>>///
84076>>>>>>>/// @Syntax ACTIVATE_TIME_STAMP of {server} to {ON/OFF}
84076>>>>>>>/// @Param server                       Name of the server
84076>>>>>>>///
84076>>>>>>>/// @Example
84076>>>>>>>/// ACTIVATE_TIME_STAMP of "localhost/orcl.localdomain" to OFF
84076>>>>>>>///
84076>>>>>>>/// SQL_SET_STMT to 'SELECT * from USER."Customer" '
84076>>>>>>>/// SQL_PREPARE_STMT
84076>>>>>>>/// SQL_EXECUTE_STMT
84076>>>>>>>/// SQL_FETCH_NEXT_ROW into sID sFirstName sLastName sDOB
84076>>>>>>>/// If (Found) Begin
84076>>>>>>>///     Showln sDOB
84076>>>>>>>/// End
84076>>>>>>>
84076>>>>>>>//=============================================================================
84076>>>>>>>/// @Name        CALL_ORACLE_STORED_FUNCTION
84076>>>>>>>/// @Description This command is used to execute a function stored in Oracle.
84076>>>>>>>/// This is an alternative to building a function with the SQL_SET_FUNCTION_NAME,
84076>>>>>>>/// SQL_SET_FUNCTION_PARAMETER and SQL_FUNCTION_EXECUTE commands. This command
84076>>>>>>>/// builds and executes the function by setting the full function name, the
84076>>>>>>>/// parameter(s) to pass and the variable to hold the returned value. Note that
84076>>>>>>>/// this command can only return a single value so SQL_SET_FUNCTION_PARAMETER
84076>>>>>>>/// and SQL_SET_FUNCTION_NAME must be used when dealing with multiple return
84076>>>>>>>/// values.
84076>>>>>>>///
84076>>>>>>>/// @Status      Deprecated
84076>>>>>>>/// @Drivers     ORAFLex
84076>>>>>>>/// @VersionNote Last Revised: 2013-10-02 by Aaron Gulack
84076>>>>>>>/// @See                 CALL_STORED_FUNCTION
84076>>>>>>>///
84076>>>>>>>/// @Syntax CALL_ORACLE_STORED_FUNCTION {function} Returns {variable} Passing {argument}
84076>>>>>>>/// @Param function                     Full name of the function
84076>>>>>>>/// @Param variable                     Variable to hold the returned value
84076>>>>>>>/// @Param argument                     Argument to pass (can be multiple)
84076>>>>>>>///
84076>>>>>>>/// @Example
84076>>>>>>>/// CALL_ORACLE_STORED_FUNCTION "user.getCustomerStatus" Returns sStatus passing sCustomerID
84076>>>>>>>/// Showln sStatus
84076>>>>>>>
84076>>>>>>>//=============================================================================
84076>>>>>>>/// @Name        CALL_PGSQL_STORED_FUNCTION
84076>>>>>>>/// @Description This command is used to execute a function stored in Oracle.
84076>>>>>>>/// This is an alternative to building a function with the SQL_SET_FUNCTION_NAME,
84076>>>>>>>/// SQL_SET_FUNCTION_PARAMETER and SQL_FUNCTION_EXECUTE commands. This command
84076>>>>>>>/// builds and executes the function by setting the full function name, the
84076>>>>>>>/// parameter(s) to pass and the variable to hold the returned value. Note that
84076>>>>>>>/// this command can only return a single value so SQL_SET_FUNCTION_PARAMETER
84076>>>>>>>/// and SQL_SET_FUNCTION_NAME must be used when dealing with multiple return
84076>>>>>>>/// values.
84076>>>>>>>///
84076>>>>>>>/// @Status      Deprecated
84076>>>>>>>/// @Drivers     PGFlex
84076>>>>>>>/// @VersionNote Last Revised: 2013-10-02 by Aaron Gulack
84076>>>>>>>/// @See                 CALL_STORED_FUNCTION
84076>>>>>>>///
84076>>>>>>>/// @Syntax CALL_PGSQL_STORED_FUNCTION {function} Returns {variable} Passing {argument}
84076>>>>>>>/// @Param function                     Full name of the function
84076>>>>>>>/// @Param variable                     Variable to hold the returned value
84076>>>>>>>/// @Param argument                     Argument to pass (can be multiple)
84076>>>>>>>///
84076>>>>>>>/// @Example
84076>>>>>>>/// CALL_PGSQL_STORED_FUNCTION "user.getCustomerStatus" Returns sStatus passing sCustomerID
84076>>>>>>>/// Showln sStatus
84076>>>>>>>
84076>>>>>>>//=============================================================================
