84076>>>>>>>/// @Syntax MERTECH_LANGUAGE_SUPPORT of {server} to {language}
84076>>>>>>>/// @Param server               The name of the server being used
84076>>>>>>>/// @Param language             The language to set support to
84076>>>>>>>
84076>>>>>>>//=============================================================================
84076>>>>>>>/// @Name        SQL_SAVE_BUFFER_BEGIN
84076>>>>>>>/// @Description This command is used to initialize a SAVE_BUFFER
84076>>>>>>>/// statement. Doing this will allow a specified set of records to be
84076>>>>>>>/// stored in the buffer before a save takes place. Once the buffer is
84076>>>>>>>/// filled, it will be saved automatically. This set of commands can be
84076>>>>>>>/// used to efficiently save a large number of records. Once the buffer
84076>>>>>>>/// is full, the save occurs automatically and the buffer will be emptied
84076>>>>>>>/// out. It is good practice to use this method inside of a transaction to
84076>>>>>>>/// maintain atomicity. Note that these commands should not be used in
84076>>>>>>>/// conjuction with finds.
84076>>>>>>>///
84076>>>>>>>/// @Assumptions
84076>>>>>>>/// @Status      Public
84076>>>>>>>/// @Drivers     All
84076>>>>>>>/// @VersionNote Last Revised: 2013-10-04 by Aaron Gulack
84076>>>>>>>/// @See         SQL_SAVE_BUFFER_END SQL_SAVE_BUFFER
84076>>>>>>>///
84076>>>>>>>/// @Syntax SQL_SAVE_BUFFER_BEGIN of {FileName} to {variable}
84076>>>>>>>/// @Param FileName                     Name of the file
84076>>>>>>>/// @Param variable                     Number of records to store in the buffer
84076>>>>>>>///
84076>>>>>>>/// @Example
84076>>>>>>>/// Open Customer
84076>>>>>>>///
84076>>>>>>>/// SQL_SAVE_BUFFER_BEGIN of Transactions to 10
84076>>>>>>>///
84076>>>>>>>/// For i from 0 to 1000
84076>>>>>>>///     Move i to Transactions.ID
84076>>>>>>>///     SQL_SAVE_BUFFER of Transactions
84076>>>>>>>/// Loop
84076>>>>>>>///
84076>>>>>>>/// SQL_SAVE_BUFFER_END of Customer
84076>>>>>>>
84076>>>>>>>//=============================================================================
84076>>>>>>>/// @Name        SQL_SAVE_BUFFER
84076>>>>>>>/// @Description This command is used to send a record to the "Save
84076>>>>>>>/// Record" buffer. It must be used along with SQL_SAVE_BUFFER_BEGIN
84076>>>>>>>/// and SQL_SAVE_BUFFER_END. SQL_SAVE_BUFFER_BEGIN sets the number of
84076>>>>>>>/// records to store in the buffer before a save is done on all the records
84076>>>>>>>/// at once. Each time a record is created, this command should be called
84076>>>>>>>/// to insert it into the buffer. Using this set of commands can be useful
84076>>>>>>>/// to efficiently save a large number of records. Once the buffer is full,
84076>>>>>>>/// the save occurs automatically and the buffer will be emptied out. It is
84076>>>>>>>/// good practice to use this method inside of a transaction to maintain
84076>>>>>>>/// atomicity.
84076>>>>>>>///
84076>>>>>>>/// @Assumptions
84076>>>>>>>/// @Status      Public
84076>>>>>>>/// @Drivers     All
84076>>>>>>>/// @VersionNote Last Revised: 2013-10-04 by Aaron Gulack
84076>>>>>>>/// @See                 SQL_SAVE_BUFFER_BEGIN SQL_SAVE_BUFFER_END
84076>>>>>>>///
84076>>>>>>>/// @Syntax SQL_SAVE_BUFFER of {FileName}
84076>>>>>>>/// @Param FileName                     Name of the file
84076>>>>>>>///
84076>>>>>>>/// @Example
84076>>>>>>>/// Open Customer
84076>>>>>>>///
84076>>>>>>>/// SQL_SAVE_BUFFER_BEGIN of Transactions to 10
84076>>>>>>>///
84076>>>>>>>/// For i from 0 to 1000
84076>>>>>>>///     Move i to Transactions.ID
84076>>>>>>>///     SQL_SAVE_BUFFER of Transactions
84076>>>>>>>/// Loop
84076>>>>>>>///
84076>>>>>>>/// SQL_SAVE_BUFFER_END of Customer
84076>>>>>>>
84076>>>>>>>//=============================================================================
84076>>>>>>>/// @Name        SQL_SAVE_BUFFER_END
84076>>>>>>>/// @Description This command indicates the end of the extended record
84076>>>>>>>/// buffer and forces a save of any data currently in the buffer.
84076>>>>>>>///
84076>>>>>>>/// @Assumptions
84076>>>>>>>/// @Status      Public
84076>>>>>>>/// @Drivers     All
84076>>>>>>>/// @VersionNote Last Revised: 2013-10-04 by Aaron Gulack
84076>>>>>>>/// @See         SQL_SAVE_BUFFER_BEGIN SQL_SAVE_BUFFER
84076>>>>>>>///
84076>>>>>>>/// @Syntax SQL_SAVE_BUFFER_END of {FileName}
84076>>>>>>>/// @Param FileName                     Name of the file
84076>>>>>>>///
84076>>>>>>>/// @Example
84076>>>>>>>/// Open Customer
84076>>>>>>>///
84076>>>>>>>/// SQL_SAVE_BUFFER_BEGIN of Transactions to 10
84076>>>>>>>///
84076>>>>>>>/// For i from 0 to 1000
84076>>>>>>>///     Move i to Transactions.ID
84076>>>>>>>///     SQL_SAVE_BUFFER of Transactions
84076>>>>>>>/// Loop
84076>>>>>>>///
84076>>>>>>>/// SQL_SAVE_BUFFER_END of Customer
84076>>>>>>>
84076>>>>>>>//=============================================================================
84076>>>>>>>/// @Name        SQL_SAVE_SET_ATTRIBUTES
84076>>>>>>>/// @Description Unknown - Not in help - Not call by any other macros
84076>>>>>>>///
84076>>>>>>>/// @Assumptions
84076>>>>>>>/// @Status      Internal
84076>>>>>>>/// @Drivers     SQLFlex
84076>>>>>>>/// @VersionNote Last Revised: 2009-08-18 By Ian Smith
84076>>>>>>>/// @See
84076>>>>>>>
84076>>>>>>>//=============================================================================
84076>>>>>>>/// @Name        ENABLE_TRACE_ON
84076>>>>>>>/// @Description This command enables driver level tracing to the
84076>>>>>>>/// specified file. Enabling trace on an application and using it
84076>>>>>>>/// in conjunction with SQL_TEXT_MESSAGE is a good way to study
84076>>>>>>>/// particular problems you encounter in the driver. SQL_TEXT_MESSAGE
84076>>>>>>>/// allows you to insert sections of your code into the trace file.
84076>>>>>>>/// This command can also set the trace to three different levels,
84076>>>>>>>/// allowing different amounts of information to be logged. Note that
84076>>>>>>>/// trace files can become very large so it is good practice to only
84076>>>>>>>/// turn them on when specifically needed.
84076>>>>>>>///
84076>>>>>>>/// @Assumptions
84076>>>>>>>/// @Status      Public
84076>>>>>>>/// @Drivers     All
84076>>>>>>>/// @VersionNote Last Revised: 2013-10-02 by Aaron Gulack
84076>>>>>>>/// @See                 DISABLE_TRACE_ON SQL_TEXT_MESSAGE
84076>>>>>>>///
84076>>>>>>>/// @Syntax ENABLE_TRACE_ON to {fileName} Debug_Level [{constant}]
84076>>>>>>>/// @Param fileName                     The path of the file to send the trace to
84076>>>>>>>/// @Param constant             DETAIL_LEVEL1, DETAIL_LEVEL2, DETAIL_LEVEL3 (optional)
84076>>>>>>>///
84076>>>>>>>/// @Example ENABLE_TRACE_ON TO "C:\Temp\trace_file.txt" Debug_Level DETAIL_LEVEL3
84076>>>>>>>
84076>>>>>>>//=============================================================================
84076>>>>>>>/// @Name        DISABLE_TRACE_ON
84076>>>>>>>/// @Description This command disables the current trace taking
84076>>>>>>>/// place on a driver.
84076>>>>>>>///
84076>>>>>>>/// @Assumptions
84076>>>>>>>/// @Status      Public
84076>>>>>>>/// @Drivers     All
84076>>>>>>>/// @VersionNote Last Revised: 2013-10-02 by Aaron Gulack
84076>>>>>>>/// @See ENABLE_TRACE_ON SQL_TEXT_MESSAGE
84076>>>>>>>///
84076>>>>>>>/// @Syntax DISABLE_TRACE_ON
84076>>>>>>>
84076>>>>>>>//=============================================================================
84076>>>>>>>/// @Name        CREATE_TABLE_FROM_DAT_FILE
84076>>>>>>>/// @Description This command is used to create a SQL table from a .DAT
84076>>>>>>>/// file. The table being copied must be not be opened in order for this
84076>>>>>>>/// command to work properly. This is the programmatic equivalent to
84076>>>>>>>/// using the Flex2SQL Migration Tool. Optional restructuring options
84076>>>>>>>/// can be specified here (see below) as well as an alternative table
84076>>>>>>>/// name than the physical name of the .DAT file. Note that this only
84076>>>>>>>/// creates the  table structure, no data will be copied here. To copy
84076>>>>>>>/// the data, use COPY_DATA after the table has been created.
84076>>>>>>>///
84076>>>>>>>/// DF_STRUCTEND_OPT_FORCE_INVK         - Deprecated
84076>>>>>>>///
84076>>>>>>>/// DF_STRUCTEND_OPT_OLD_INVK_NAME      - Deprecated
84076>>>>>>>///
84076>>>>>>>/// DF_STRUCTEND_OPT_FORCE_NOT_NULL - forces all fields to be created as NOT NULL.
84076>>>>>>>///
84076>>>>>>>/// @Assumptions
84076>>>>>>>/// @Status      Public
84076>>>>>>>/// @Drivers     All
84076>>>>>>>/// @VersionNote Last Revised: 2013-10-09 by Aaron Gulack
84076>>>>>>>/// @See                 COPY_DATA CONVERT_DAT_FILE
84076>>>>>>>///
84076>>>>>>>/// @Syntax CREATE_TABLE_FROM_DAT_FILE {FileNumber} [{options} {table}]
84076>>>>>>>/// @Param FileNumber           Number of the file
84076>>>>>>>/// @Param options                      DF_STRUCTEND_OPT_FORCE_INVK
84076>>>>>>>///                                                     DF_STRUCTEND_OPT_OLD_INVK_NAME
84076>>>>>>>///                                                     DF_STRUCTEND_OPT_FORCE_NOT_NULL (optional)
84076>>>>>>>/// @Param table            name of table to use instead of physical name (optional)
84076>>>>>>>///
84076>>>>>>>/// @Example
84076>>>>>>>/// Login "localhost" "user" "pass123" "sql_drv"
84076>>>>>>>/// CREATE_TABLE_FROM_DAT_FILE Customer.File_Number "Customer"
84076>>>>>>>/// COPY_DATA "Customer" to "sql_drv:Customer" CALLBACK (Callback(Self)) CONSTRAIN "STATUS = 'Active'"
84076>>>>>>>
84076>>>>>>>//=============================================================================
84076>>>>>>>/// @Name        CONVERT_DAT_FILE
84076>>>>>>>/// @Description This command is the programmatic equivalent to the
84076>>>>>>>/// Flex2SQL Migration Tool. With this command, a SQL table can be
84076>>>>>>>/// created from a .DAT table. This combines the COPY_DATA and
84076>>>>>>>/// CREATE_TABLE_FROM_DAT_FILE, creating the table structure and
84076>>>>>>>/// copying all the data into the new table with one command. The
84076>>>>>>>/// table being converted cannot be opened and so a manual login is
84076>>>>>>>/// needed. Note that to specify the database to copy the table to,
84076>>>>>>>/// use SET_DATABASE_NAME. Below is a list of the optional restructure
84076>>>>>>>/// options to use when creating the table.
84076>>>>>>>///
84076>>>>>>>/// DF_STRUCTEND_OPT_FORCE_INVK         - Deprecated
84076>>>>>>>///
84076>>>>>>>/// DF_STRUCTEND_OPT_OLD_INVK_NAME      - Deprecated
84076>>>>>>>///
84076>>>>>>>/// DF_STRUCTEND_OPT_FORCE_NOT_NULL - forces all fields to be created as NOT NULL.
84076>>>>>>>///
84076>>>>>>>/// @Assumptions
84076>>>>>>>/// @Status      Public
84076>>>>>>>/// @Drivers     All
84076>>>>>>>/// @VersionNote Last Revised: 2013-10-09 by Aaron Gulack
84076>>>>>>>/// @See                 CREATE_TABLE_FROM_DAT_FILE COPY_DATA
84076>>>>>>>///
84076>>>>>>>/// @Syntax CONVERT_DAT_FILE {FileNumber} [{options} {table}]
84076>>>>>>>/// @Param FileNumber           Number of the file
84076>>>>>>>/// @Param options                      DF_STRUCTEND_OPT_FORCE_INVK
84076>>>>>>>///                                                     DF_STRUCTEND_OPT_OLD_INVK_NAME
84076>>>>>>>///                                                     DF_STRUCTEND_OPT_FORCE_NOT_NULL (optional)
84076>>>>>>>/// @Param table            Name of table to use instead of physical name (optional)
84076>>>>>>>///
84076>>>>>>>/// @Example
84076>>>>>>>/// Login "localhost" "user" "pass123" "sql_drv"
84076>>>>>>>/// CONVERT_DAT_FILE Customer.File_Number DF_STRUCTEND_OPT_FORCE_NOT_NULL "Customer"
84076>>>>>>>
84076>>>>>>>//=============================================================================
84076>>>>>>>/// @Name        SET_DEFAULT_FILE_CASING
84076>>>>>>>/// @Description This command is used to set the file casing standard when
84076>>>>>>>/// creating or restructuring tables. By default, all table and column names
84076>>>>>>>/// are created using the specified casing. Passing FILE_CASING_UPPER or
84076>>>>>>>/// FILE_CASING_LOWER will allow the names to be saved in uppercase or
84076>>>>>>>/// lowercase respectively. This can be useful for backwards compatibility
84076>>>>>>>/// where casing was important. Note that the casing standard for a file can
84076>>>>>>>/// also be changed through mertech.ini. Below is a description of the constants
84076>>>>>>>/// that can be passed to this command.
84076>>>>>>>///
84076>>>>>>>/// FILE_CASING_UPPER : All created or edited object names will be converted to uppercase.
84076>>>>>>>/// FILE_CASING_LOWER : All created or edited object names will be converted to lowercase.
84076>>>>>>>/// FILE_CASING_KEEP (default) : All created or edited object names will maintain their inputed casing.
84076>>>>>>>///
84076>>>>>>>/// @Assumptions
84076>>>>>>>/// @Status      Public
84076>>>>>>>/// @Drivers     All
84076>>>>>>>/// @VersionNote Last Revised: 2013-10-07 by Aaron Gulack
84076>>>>>>>/// @See                 GET_DEFAULT_FILE_CASING
84076>>>>>>>///
84076>>>>>>>/// @Syntax SET_DEFAULT_FILE_CASING to {constant}
84076>>>>>>>/// @Param constant                     FILE_CASING_UPPER, FILE_CASING_LOWER, FILE_CASING_KEEP
84076>>>>>>>///
84076>>>>>>>/// @Example
84076>>>>>>>/// SET_DEFAULT_FILE_CASING to FILE_CASING_UPPER
84076>>>>>>>
84076>>>>>>>//=============================================================================
84076>>>>>>>/// @Name        GET_DEFAULT_FILE_CASING
84076>>>>>>>/// @Description This command returns the file casing standard used
84076>>>>>>>/// when creating or restructuring tables. Note that an integer is returned,
84076>>>>>>>/// mapping to a casing method. Below are the meanings of the possible
84076>>>>>>>/// returned integers.
84076>>>>>>>///
84076>>>>>>>/// 0 - FILE_CASING_UPPER : All created or edited object names will be converted to uppercase.
84076>>>>>>>/// 1 - FILE_CASING_LOWER : All created or edited object names will be converted to lowercase.
84076>>>>>>>/// 2 - FILE_CASING_KEEP : All created or edited object names will maintain their inputed casing.
84076>>>>>>>///
84076>>>>>>>/// @Assumptions
84076>>>>>>>/// @Status      Public
84076>>>>>>>/// @Drivers     All
84076>>>>>>>/// @VersionNote Last Revised: 2013-10-07 by Aaron Gulack
84076>>>>>>>/// @See                 SET_DEFAULT_FILE_CASING
84076>>>>>>>///
84076>>>>>>>/// @Syntax GET_DEFAULT_FILE_CASING to {variable}
84076>>>>>>>/// @Param variable                     Variable to hold the returned casing
84076>>>>>>>///
84076>>>>>>>/// @Example
84076>>>>>>>/// GET_DEFAULT_FILE_CASING TO iCasing
84076>>>>>>>
84076>>>>>>>//=============================================================================
84076>>>>>>>/// @Name        SET_DEFAULT_TABLESPACE
84076>>>>>>>/// @Description This command sets the default table space to use when
84076>>>>>>>/// creating tables through Dataflex. A tablespace is a container of
84076>>>>>>>/// segments (objects that have an allotted amount of space), i.e. tables
84076>>>>>>>/// and indexes.
84076>>>>>>>///
84076>>>>>>>/// @Assumptions
84076>>>>>>>/// @Status      Public
84076>>>>>>>/// @Drivers     ORAFlex, PgFlex
84076>>>>>>>/// @VersionNote Last Revised: 2013-10-09 by Aaron Gulack
84076>>>>>>>/// @See                 GET_DEFAULT_TABLESPACE SET_DEFAULT_INDEX_TABLESPACE GET_DEFAULT_INDEX_TABLESPACE
84076>>>>>>>///
84076>>>>>>>/// @Syntax SET_DEFAULT_TABLESPACE to {variable}
84076>>>>>>>/// @Param variable                     Name of the default table space
84076>>>>>>>///
84076>>>>>>>/// @Example
84076>>>>>>>/// SET_DEFAULT_TABLESPACE to "Users"
84076>>>>>>>
84076>>>>>>>//=============================================================================
84076>>>>>>>/// @Name        GET_DEFAULT_TABLESPACE
84076>>>>>>>/// @Description This command returns the default table space name for
84076>>>>>>>/// the current database.
84076>>>>>>>///
84076>>>>>>>/// @Assumptions
84076>>>>>>>/// @Status      Public
84076>>>>>>>/// @Drivers     ORAFlex, PgFlex
84076>>>>>>>/// @VersionNote Last Revised: 2013-10-09 by Aaron Gulack
84076>>>>>>>/// @See                 SET_DEFAULT_TABLESPACE SET_DEFAULT_INDEX_TABLESPACE GET_DEFAULT_INDEX_TABLESPACE
84076>>>>>>>///
84076>>>>>>>/// @Syntax GET_DEFAULT_TABLESPACE to {variable}
84076>>>>>>>/// @Param variable                     Variable to hold the default table space name.
84076>>>>>>>///
84076>>>>>>>/// @Example
84076>>>>>>>/// GET_DEFAULT_TABLESPACE to sTableSpace
84076>>>>>>>
84076>>>>>>>//=============================================================================
84076>>>>>>>/// @Name        SET_DEFAULT_INDEX_TABLESPACE
84076>>>>>>>/// @Description This command sets the default table space for indexes
84076>>>>>>>/// when creating tables through the DataFlex API. A tablespace is a
84076>>>>>>>/// container of segments (objects that have an allotted amount of space),
84076>>>>>>>/// i.e. tables and indexes.
84076>>>>>>>///
84076>>>>>>>/// @Assumptions
84076>>>>>>>/// @Status      Public
84076>>>>>>>/// @Drivers     ORAFlex, PgFlex
84076>>>>>>>/// @VersionNote Last Revised: 2013-10-09-2013 by Aaron Gulack
84076>>>>>>>/// @See                 SET_DEFAULT_TABLESPACE GET_DEFAULT_TABLESPACE GET_DEFAULT_INDEX_TABLESPACE
84076>>>>>>>///
84076>>>>>>>/// @Syntax SET_DEFAULT_INDEX_TABLESPACE to {variable}
84076>>>>>>>/// @Param variable                     Variable to hold the default index table space name.
84076>>>>>>>///
84076>>>>>>>/// @Example
84076>>>>>>>/// SET_DEFAULT_INDEX_TABLESPACE to "Users"
84076>>>>>>>
84076>>>>>>>//=============================================================================
84076>>>>>>>/// @Name        GET_DEFAULT_INDEX_TABLESPACE
84076>>>>>>>/// @Description This command returns the default table space name for
