84123>>>>>>>/// @Name        SQL_ESCAPE_STRING
84123>>>>>>>/// @Description This command is used to properly escape strings before
84123>>>>>>>/// they are used in embedded SQL statements. This can be extremely
84123>>>>>>>/// important when you do not have full control of the strings being passed
84123>>>>>>>/// to the SQL statement as this will ensure that the strings are properly
84123>>>>>>>/// quoted.
84123>>>>>>>///
84123>>>>>>>/// @Assumptions
84123>>>>>>>/// @Status      Public
84123>>>>>>>/// @Drivers     All
84123>>>>>>>/// @VersionNote Last Revised: 2013-10-02 by Aaron Gulack
84123>>>>>>>/// @See
84123>>>>>>>///
84123>>>>>>>/// @Syntax SQL_ESCAPE_STRING of {string} to {variable}
84123>>>>>>>/// @Param string               The string to be escaped.
84123>>>>>>>/// @Param variable     Variable to hold the newly escaped string
84123>>>>>>>///
84123>>>>>>>/// @Example
84123>>>>>>>/// SQL_ESCAPE_STRING of "They said to me, 'hello'." to sEscaped
84123>>>>>>>
84123>>>>>>>Function SQLESCAPESTRING Global String sData Returns String
84125>>>>>>>    String sReturnData
84125>>>>>>>
84125>>>>>>>    DO_GETFILENUMBER_DRIVERNAME 0
84127>>>>>>>
84127>>>>>>>    If (MertechInc_FileNumber <> -1) Begin
84129>>>>>>>        Get MertechInc_Pre_Size_String 0 to sReturnData
84130>>>>>>>        Call_Driver 0 MertechInc_DriverName Function CALLDRV_ESCAPE_STRING CALLBACK 0 PASSING sData sReturnData 0 RESULT MertechInc_iRet
84135>>>>>>>    End
84135>>>>>>>>
84135>>>>>>>
84135>>>>>>>    Function_Return sReturnData
84136>>>>>>>End_Function
84137>>>>>>>
84137>>>>>>>//=============================================================================
84137>>>>>>>/// @Name        DIRECT_PATH_LOAD
84137>>>>>>>/// @Description
84137>>>>>>>///
84137>>>>>>>/// @Assumptions
84137>>>>>>>/// @Status      Internal
84137>>>>>>>/// @Drivers     OraFlex
84137>>>>>>>/// @VersionNote Last Revised: 2009-09-21 By Ian Smith
84137>>>>>>>/// @See
84137>>>>>>>
84137>>>>>>>//=============================================================================
84137>>>>>>>/// @Name        SQL_INITIALIZE_SEQUENCE
84137>>>>>>>/// @Description This command is used to initialize all auto increment
84137>>>>>>>/// columns, or sequences in Oracle, of the specified table to be the
84137>>>>>>>/// highest number plus one. This is useful when inserting a large amount
84137>>>>>>>/// of records in the table and the sequence is not being updated because
84137>>>>>>>/// the auto incremented column is being manually filled.
84137>>>>>>>///
84137>>>>>>>/// @Assumptions
84137>>>>>>>/// @Status      Public
84137>>>>>>>/// @Drivers     OraFlex PgFlex
84137>>>>>>>/// @VersionNote Last Revised: 2013-10-09 by Aaron Gulack
84137>>>>>>>/// @See
84137>>>>>>>///
84137>>>>>>>/// SQL_INITIALIZE_SEQUENCE of {FileNumber}
84137>>>>>>>/// @Param FileNumber                   The file number
84137>>>>>>>
84137>>>>>>>//=============================================================================
84137>>>>>>>/// @Name        LOB_APPEND
84137>>>>>>>/// @Description This command is used to append data to an existing LOB
84137>>>>>>>/// column in the database. When called, the data corresponding field
84137>>>>>>>/// in the buffer is appended to the respective column in the database.
84137>>>>>>>/// This can be very useful when saving data that exceeds VDF size limits
84137>>>>>>>/// but falls within the limits of the SQL database. Note that this command
84137>>>>>>>/// must write to a file that is active and locked. Also the save is handled
84137>>>>>>>/// within the command so no extra calls are needed to save the changes made.
84137>>>>>>>///
84137>>>>>>>/// @Assumptions The field being used is a LOB field
84137>>>>>>>/// @Status      Deprecated
84137>>>>>>>/// @Drivers     All
84137>>>>>>>/// @VersionNote Last Revised: 2013-10-02 by Aaron Gulack
84137>>>>>>>/// @See                 SQL_LOB_ADD_CHUNK
84137>>>>>>>///
84137>>>>>>>/// @Syntax LOB_APPEND of {FileName} {FieldNumber}
84137>>>>>>>/// @Param FileName                     Name of the file containing the LOB column
84137>>>>>>>/// @Param FieldNumber          Number of the field being appended to
84137>>>>>>>///
84137>>>>>>>/// @Example
84137>>>>>>>/// Clear Customer
84137>>>>>>>/// Find Gt Customer By Index.1
84137>>>>>>>///
84137>>>>>>>/// Direct_Input 'C:\Mertech.xml'
84137>>>>>>>/// Lock
84137>>>>>>>///    Find Eq Customer by Recnum
84137>>>>>>>///
84137>>>>>>>///    Read_Block Customer.Comments 16384
84137>>>>>>>///    SQL_LOB_WRITE of Customer 13 // Customer.Comments
84137>>>>>>>///    Repeat
84137>>>>>>>///        Read_Block Customer.Comments 16384
84137>>>>>>>///        SQL_LOB_APPEND of Customer 13 // Customer.Comments
84137>>>>>>>///    Until (SeqEOF)
84137>>>>>>>/// Unlock
84137>>>>>>>///
84137>>>>>>>/// Close_Input
84137>>>>>>>/// Find Eq Customer By Recnum
84137>>>>>>>/// SQL_LOB_LENGTH of Customer 13 to iLength
84137>>>>>>>/// Showln 'Length: ' iLength
84137>>>>>>>
84137>>>>>>>
84137>>>>>>>//=============================================================================
84137>>>>>>>/// @Name        LOB_LENGTH
84137>>>>>>>/// @Description This command returns the length of the data in the
84137>>>>>>>/// specified column. This command must be used after a proper FIND to
84137>>>>>>>/// ensure that a valid record is in the buffer. This can be a useful
84137>>>>>>>/// command for checking if uploaded data exceeds size limits.
84137>>>>>>>///
84137>>>>>>>/// @Assumptions The field being used is a LOB field
84137>>>>>>>/// @Status      Deprecated
84137>>>>>>>/// @Drivers     All
84137>>>>>>>/// @VersionNote Last Revised: 2013-10-02 by Aaron Gulack
84137>>>>>>>/// @See                 SQL_GET_LOB_LENGTH
84137>>>>>>>///
84137>>>>>>>/// @Syntax LOB_LENGTH of {FileName} {FieldNumber} to {variable}
84137>>>>>>>/// @Param FileName                     Name of the file
84137>>>>>>>/// @Param FieldNumber          Number of the LOB field
84137>>>>>>>/// @Param variable                     Variable to hold the length
84137>>>>>>>///
84137>>>>>>>/// @Example
84137>>>>>>>/// Clear Customer
84137>>>>>>>/// Find Gt Customer By Index.1
84137>>>>>>>/// SQL_LOB_LENGTH of Customer 13 to iLength
84137>>>>>>>/// Showln 'Length: ' iLength
84137>>>>>>>
84137>>>>>>>
84137>>>>>>>//=============================================================================
84137>>>>>>>/// @Name        LOB_READ
84137>>>>>>>/// @Description This command reads a chunk of data from a specified LOB
84137>>>>>>>/// column, moving it into its corresponding field buffer. Because the
84137>>>>>>>/// chunk will be moved into the field buffer, it can only be as large as
84137>>>>>>>/// the buffer allows. To account for this, the constants FIRST or NEXT
84137>>>>>>>/// are passed as well indicating whether to grab the first chunk for
84137>>>>>>>/// the buffer or the next. Each chunk grabbed will be as large as allowed.
84137>>>>>>>/// All these things considered, when reading data larger than the field
84137>>>>>>>/// buffer, it is good practice to perform the read in a loop, adding the
84137>>>>>>>/// length each time. Another optional parameter that can be passed is a
84137>>>>>>>/// variable that will store the length of the chunk. Note that a LOB read
84137>>>>>>>/// must be done after a successful find on the record.
84137>>>>>>>///
84137>>>>>>>/// @Assumptions The field being used is a LOB field
84137>>>>>>>/// @Status      Deprecated
84137>>>>>>>/// @Drivers     All
84137>>>>>>>/// @VersionNote Last Revised: 2013-10-02 by Aaron Gulack
84137>>>>>>>/// @See                 SQL_GET_LOB SQL_GET_LOB_CHUNK
84137>>>>>>>///
84137>>>>>>>/// @Syntax LOB_READ of {FileName} {FieldNumber} {FIRST/NEXT} [{length}]
84137>>>>>>>/// @Param FileName                     Name of the file containing the LOB field
84137>>>>>>>/// @Param FieldNumber          Number of the field being read from
84137>>>>>>>/// @Param FIRST                        Reads the first chunk of data
84137>>>>>>>/// @Param NEXT                         Reads the next chuck of data (if larger than buffer limit)
84137>>>>>>>/// @Param length                       Variable to hold the chunk length (optional)
84137>>>>>>>///
84137>>>>>>>/// @Example
84137>>>>>>>/// Direct_Output ('binary:Mertech.pdf')
84137>>>>>>>///
84137>>>>>>>/// Clear customer
84137>>>>>>>/// Find Gt customer by Index.1
84137>>>>>>>/// SQL_LOB_LENGTH of customer 13 to liLength
84137>>>>>>>///
84137>>>>>>>/// While (liLength > 0)
84137>>>>>>>///     Write customer.comments
84137>>>>>>>///     SQL_LOB_READ of customer 13 Next liLength
84137>>>>>>>/// Loop
84137>>>>>>>///
84137>>>>>>>/// Close_Output
84137>>>>>>>
84137>>>>>>>
84137>>>>>>>//=============================================================================
84137>>>>>>>/// @Name        LOB_WRITE
84137>>>>>>>/// @Description This command is used to write data to a LOB column.
84137>>>>>>>/// By passing the file name and field number of the LOB column, this
84137>>>>>>>/// command will take the current value of the respective field in
84137>>>>>>>/// the field buffer, write it to the database and save it. Any data
84137>>>>>>>/// currently in that field will be overridden by the data from the
84137>>>>>>>/// buffer. Note that this command must write to a file that is active
84137>>>>>>>/// and locked. Also this command handles the save so no extra calls
84137>>>>>>>/// are needed to save the changes.
84137>>>>>>>///
84137>>>>>>>/// @Assumptions The field being used is a LOB field
84137>>>>>>>/// @Status      Deprecated
84137>>>>>>>/// @Drivers     All
84137>>>>>>>/// @VersionNote Last Revised: 2013-10-02 by Aaron Gulack
84137>>>>>>>/// @See                 SQL_SET_LOB SQL_ADD_LOB_CHUNK
84137>>>>>>>///
84137>>>>>>>/// @Syntax LOB_WRITE of {FileName} {FieldNumber}
84137>>>>>>>/// @Param FileName                     Name of the file containing the LOB field
84137>>>>>>>/// @Param FieldNumber          Number of the field being written to
84137>>>>>>>///
84137>>>>>>>/// @Example
84137>>>>>>>/// Clear Customer
84137>>>>>>>/// Find Gt Customer By Index.1
84137>>>>>>>///
84137>>>>>>>/// Direct_Input 'C:\Mertech.xml'
84137>>>>>>>/// Lock
84137>>>>>>>///    Find Eq Customer by Recnum
84137>>>>>>>///
84137>>>>>>>///    Read_Block Customer.Comments 16384
84137>>>>>>>///    SQL_LOB_WRITE of Customer 13 // Customer.Comments
84137>>>>>>>///    Repeat
84137>>>>>>>///        Read_Block Customer.Comments 16384
84137>>>>>>>///        SQL_LOB_APPEND of Customer 13 // Customer.Comments
84137>>>>>>>///    Until (SeqEOF)
84137>>>>>>>/// Unlock
84137>>>>>>>/// Close_Input
84137>>>>>>>///
84137>>>>>>>/// Find Eq Customer By Recnum
84137>>>>>>>/// SQL_LOB_LENGTH of Customer 13 to iLength
84137>>>>>>>/// Showln 'Length: ' iLength
84137>>>>>>>
84137>>>>>>>
84137>>>>>>>//=============================================================================
84137>>>>>>>/// @Name        LOB_LOADFROMFILE
84137>>>>>>>/// @Description This command loads an external file into a specified LOB
84137>>>>>>>/// column. After specifying the file name and field number, the path and
84137>>>>>>>/// file must then be passed respectively. When using Oracle, instead of
84137>>>>>>>/// passing the directory, a directory alias must be passed. This alias
84137>>>>>>>/// can be created using a "CREATE DIRECTORY" statement in SQL. For more
84137>>>>>>>/// information on setting this directory alias, see the Oracle help.
84137>>>>>>>/// For other servers, the file must be a local file available to the
84137>>>>>>>/// application that is calling the command. Note that this command must
84137>>>>>>>/// write to a file that is active and locked. Also this command handles
84137>>>>>>>/// the save so no extra calls are needed to save the changes.
84137>>>>>>>///
84137>>>>>>>/// @Assumptions The field being used is a LOB field
84137>>>>>>>/// @Status      Deprecated
84137>>>>>>>/// @Drivers     All
84137>>>>>>>/// @VersionNote Last Revised: 2013-10-02 by Aaron Gulack
84137>>>>>>>/// @See                 LOB_APPEND LOB_LENGTH LOB_WRITE LOB_READ LOB_ERASE LOB_TRUNCATE FLUSH_LOB_BUFFER
84137>>>>>>>///
84137>>>>>>>/// @Syntax LOB_LOADFROMFILE of {FileName} {FieldNumber} From {path} {file}
84137>>>>>>>/// @Param FileName                     Name of the file containing the LOB column
84137>>>>>>>/// @Param FieldNumber          Number of the LOB column being used
84137>>>>>>>/// @Param path                         The path of the file, excluding the file name
84137>>>>>>>/// @Param file                         The name of the file, including the extension
84137>>>>>>>///
84137>>>>>>>/// @Example
84137>>>>>>>/// Clear Customer
84137>>>>>>>/// Find Gt Customer By Index.1
84137>>>>>>>/// Lock
84137>>>>>>>///    Find Eq Customer by Recnum
84137>>>>>>>///    LOB_TRUNCATE OF customel 13 to 0 // Customer.Comments
84137>>>>>>>///    Saverecord Customer
84137>>>>>>>///    // Directory name is case sensitive.
84137>>>>>>>///    // Make sure the name case matches
84137>>>>>>>///    LOB_LOADFROMFILE OF customel 13 FROM "C:\Mertech\FilesToLoad" "Mertech.XML"
84137>>>>>>>/// Unlock
84137>>>>>>>
84137>>>>>>>
84137>>>>>>>//=============================================================================
84137>>>>>>>/// @Name        LOB_ERASE
84137>>>>>>>/// @Description This command is used to erase a portion of data from a
84137>>>>>>>/// LOB column. For text fields, the portion of data to be erased is
84137>>>>>>>/// replaced with white space, and in binary fields, with 0X0. To erase
84137>>>>>>>/// a portion of the data, pass the length to erase as well as the number
84137>>>>>>>/// to offset from. For this command to work properly, it must be done
84137>>>>>>>/// after a valid find. Note that the save is handled inside this command
84137>>>>>>>/// so no extra commands are needed to save the changes.
84137>>>>>>>///
84137>>>>>>>/// @Assumptions The field being used is a LOB field
84137>>>>>>>/// @Status      Deprecated
84137>>>>>>>/// @Drivers     All
84137>>>>>>>/// @VersionNote Last Revised: 2013-10-02 by Aaron Gulack
84137>>>>>>>/// @See LOB_APPEND LOB_LENGTH LOB_WRITE LOB_READ LOB_LOADFROMFILE LOB_ERASE LOB_TRUNCATE FLUSH_LOB_BUFFER
84137>>>>>>>///
84137>>>>>>>/// @Syntax LOB_ERASE OF {FileName} {FieldNumber} {length} {offset}
84137>>>>>>>/// @Param FileName                     Name of the file containing the LOB column
84137>>>>>>>/// @Param FieldNumber          Number of the LOB column being erased
84137>>>>>>>/// @Param Length                       Length of chunk to erase from column
84137>>>>>>>/// @Param offset                       Starting position for erase
84137>>>>>>>///
84137>>>>>>>/// @Example
84137>>>>>>>/// Clear customer
84137>>>>>>>/// Find Gt customer by Recnum
84137>>>>>>>/// Lock
84137>>>>>>>/// Find Eq customer by Recnum
84137>>>>>>>/// LOB_LENGTH OF customer 13 to liTotalLength
84137>>>>>>>/// LOB_ERASE  OF customer 13    liTotalLength 1
84137>>>>>>>/// Unlock
84137>>>>>>>
84137>>>>>>>
84137>>>>>>>//=============================================================================
84137>>>>>>>/// @Name        LOB_TRUNCATE
84137>>>>>>>/// @Description This command is used to trim a LOB column down to a
84137>>>>>>>/// specified length. By passing the table name and column number, the
84137>>>>>>>/// value in the column can then be trimmed down the specified length.
84137>>>>>>>/// This can be a useful command for clearing out a column before entering
84137>>>>>>>/// new data into it. Note that this command must write to a file that is active
84137>>>>>>>/// and locked. Also this command handles the save so no extra calls
84137>>>>>>>/// are needed to save the changes. This command can be used to clear out a field before adding new data
84137>>>>>>>///
84137>>>>>>>/// @Assumptions The field being used is a LOB field
84137>>>>>>>/// @Status      Deprecated
84137>>>>>>>/// @Drivers     All
84137>>>>>>>/// @VersionNote Last Revised: 2013-10-02 by Aaron Gulack
84137>>>>>>>/// @See                 LOB_APPEND LOB_LENGTH LOB_WRITE LOB_READ LOB_LOADFROMFILE LOB_ERASE FLUSH_LOB_BUFFER
84137>>>>>>>///
84137>>>>>>>/// @Syntax LOB_TRUNCATE of {FileName} {FieldNumber} to {variable}
84137>>>>>>>/// @Param FileName                     Name of the file
84137>>>>>>>/// @Param FieldNumber          The field number
84137>>>>>>>/// @Param length                       New length to truncate to
84137>>>>>>>///
84137>>>>>>>/// @Example
84137>>>>>>>/// Clear Customer
84137>>>>>>>/// Find Gt Customer By Index.1
84137>>>>>>>/// Lock
84137>>>>>>>///    Find Eq Customer by Recnum
84137>>>>>>>///    SQL_LOB_TRUNCATE of Customer 13 to 0 // Customer.Comments
84137>>>>>>>///    Saverecord Customer
84137>>>>>>>/// Unlock
84137>>>>>>>
84137>>>>>>>
84137>>>>>>>//=============================================================================
84137>>>>>>>/// @Name        FLUSH_LOB_BUFFER
84137>>>>>>>/// @Description This command currently serves no function.
84137>>>>>>>///
84137>>>>>>>/// @Assumptions
84137>>>>>>>/// @Status      Deprecated
84137>>>>>>>/// @Drivers     MySQLFlex
84137>>>>>>>/// @VersionNote Last Revised: 2013-10-08 by Aaron Gulack
84137>>>>>>>/// @See
84137>>>>>>>///
84137>>>>>>>/// @Syntax FLUSH_LOB_BUFFER of {FileName}
84137>>>>>>>/// @Param FileName                     Name of the file
84137>>>>>>>
84137>>>>>>>
