84137>>>>>>>//=============================================================================
84137>>>>>>>/// @Name        CALL_MYSQL_STORED_PROCEDURE
84137>>>>>>>/// @Description This command is used to call a stored procedure on the SQL
84137>>>>>>>/// backend. To successfully call a procedure with this command, a string
84137>>>>>>>/// must be passed containing a valid procedure name. In addition, if the
84137>>>>>>>/// procedure takes any arguments, they must also be passed using the constant
84137>>>>>>>/// "passing" along with all of the needed arguments. If the procedure has a
84137>>>>>>>/// return value, then SQL_GET_FUNCTION_RETURN or SQL_FETCH_NEXT_ROW can be
84137>>>>>>>/// used to get the value(s). If an error is found then the indicator "Err"
84137>>>>>>>/// is set to true.
84137>>>>>>>///
84137>>>>>>>/// @Assumptions
84137>>>>>>>/// @Status      Deprecated
84137>>>>>>>/// @Drivers     MySQLFlex
84137>>>>>>>/// @VersionNote Last Revised: 2013-10-02 by Aaron Gulack
84137>>>>>>>/// @See                 CALL_STORED_PROCEDURE
84137>>>>>>>///
84137>>>>>>>/// @Syntax CALL_MYSQL_STORED_PROCEDURE {procedure} Passing {argument}
84137>>>>>>>/// @Param procedure            Full name of the procedure
84137>>>>>>>/// @Param argument                     Argument to pass (can be multiple)
84137>>>>>>>///
84137>>>>>>>/// @Example
84137>>>>>>>/// CALL_MYSQL_STORED_PROCEDURE "getCustomerStatus" passing sCustomerID sStatus
84137>>>>>>>/// SQL_GET_PROCEDURE_PARAMETER 2 to sStatus
84137>>>>>>>/// Showln sStatus
84137>>>>>>>
84137>>>>>>>//=============================================================================
84137>>>>>>>/// @Name        CALL_MYSQL_STORED_FUNCTION
84137>>>>>>>/// @Description This command is used to execute a function stored in MySQL.
84137>>>>>>>/// This is an alternative to building a function with the SQL_SET_FUNCTION_NAME,
84137>>>>>>>/// SQL_SET_FUNCTION_PARAMETER and SQL_FUNCTION_EXECUTE commands. This command
84137>>>>>>>/// builds and executes the function by setting the full function name, the
84137>>>>>>>/// parameter(s) to pass and the variable to hold the returned value. Note that
84137>>>>>>>/// this command can only return a single value so SQL_SET_FUNCTION_PARAMETER
84137>>>>>>>/// and SQL_SET_FUNCTION_NAME must be used when dealing with multiple return
84137>>>>>>>/// values.
84137>>>>>>>///
84137>>>>>>>/// @Status      Deprecated
84137>>>>>>>/// @Drivers     MySQLFlex
84137>>>>>>>/// @VersionNote Last Revised: 2013-10-02 by Aaron Gulack
84137>>>>>>>/// @See                 CALL_STORED_FUNCTION
84137>>>>>>>///
84137>>>>>>>/// @Syntax CALL_MYSQL_STORED_FUNCTION {function} Returns {variable} Passing {argument}
84137>>>>>>>/// @Param function                     Full name of the function
84137>>>>>>>/// @Param variable                     Variable to hold the returned value
84137>>>>>>>/// @Param argument                     Argument to pass (can be multiple)
84137>>>>>>>///
84137>>>>>>>/// @Example
84137>>>>>>>/// CALL_MYSQL_STORED_FUNCTION "getCustomerStatus" Returns sStatus passing sCustomerID
84137>>>>>>>/// Showln sStatus
84137>>>>>>>
84137>>>>>>>//=============================================================================
84137>>>>>>>/// @Name        DO_SET_ALL_FUNCTION_PARAMETERS
84137>>>>>>>/// @Description Sets the parameters for a MySQL stored function call.
84137>>>>>>>///
84137>>>>>>>/// @Assumptions
84137>>>>>>>/// @Status      Internal
84137>>>>>>>/// @Drivers     MySQLFlex
84137>>>>>>>/// @VersionNote Last Revised: 2009-09-21 By Ian Smith
84137>>>>>>>/// @See
84137>>>>>>>///
84137>>>>>>>/// @Syntax DO_SET_ALL_FUNCTION_PARAMETERS [sParam1 [sParam2 . sParamn]]
84137>>>>>>>/// @Param sParam1.n    Parameters for the stored function
84137>>>>>>>
84137>>>>>>>//=============================================================================
84137>>>>>>>/// @Name        GET_NO_AVAILABLE_SQLSERVERS
84137>>>>>>>/// @Description This command is used to get the number of available MSSQL
84137>>>>>>>/// servers detected in the network. When used with GET_SQLSERVER_NAME,
84137>>>>>>>/// all the available server names can be easily retrieved.
84137>>>>>>>///
84137>>>>>>>/// @Assumptions SQL Server Browser Service is started and firewall is configured properly
84137>>>>>>>/// @Status      Public
84137>>>>>>>/// @Drivers     SQLFlex
84137>>>>>>>/// @VersionNote Last Revised: 2013-10-02 by Aaron Gulack
84137>>>>>>>/// @See                 GET_SQLSERVER_NAME
84137>>>>>>>///
84137>>>>>>>/// @Syntax GET_NO_AVAILABLE_SQLSERVERS to {variable}
84137>>>>>>>/// @Param variable                     Variable to hold number of servers
84137>>>>>>>///
84137>>>>>>>/// @Example
84137>>>>>>>/// GET_NO_AVAILABLE_SQLSERVERS to iServers
84137>>>>>>>///
84137>>>>>>>/// While (i <= iServers)
84137>>>>>>>///     GET_SQLSERVER_NAME i to sServer
84137>>>>>>>///     Showln sServer
84137>>>>>>>///     Increment i
84137>>>>>>>/// Loop
84137>>>>>>>
84137>>>>>>>Function SQL_AVAILABLE_SQL_SERVERS Global Returns Integer
84139>>>>>>>    Call_Driver 0 SQLFLEX Function CALLDRV_ENUMERATE_SERVER CALLBACK 0 PASSING MertechInc_Blank MertechInc_Blank CALLDRV_ENUMERATE_SERVER_COUNT RESULT MertechInc_iRet
84144>>>>>>>
84144>>>>>>>    Function_Return MertechInc_iRet
84145>>>>>>>End_Function
84146>>>>>>>
84146>>>>>>>
84146>>>>>>>//=============================================================================
84146>>>>>>>/// @Name        GET_SQLSERVER_NAME
84146>>>>>>>/// @Description This command returns the name of the server based on the
84146>>>>>>>/// specified index number. The number of servers can be retrieved from
84146>>>>>>>/// GET_NO_AVAILABLE_SQLSERVERS and the names can be indexed from that
84146>>>>>>>/// number.
84146>>>>>>>///
84146>>>>>>>/// @Assumptions SQL Server Browser Service is started and firewall is configured properly
84146>>>>>>>/// @Status      Public
84146>>>>>>>/// @Drivers     SQLFlex
84146>>>>>>>/// @VersionNote Last Revised: 2013-10-02 by Aaron Gulack
84146>>>>>>>/// @See                 GET_NO_AVAILABLE_SQLSERVERS
84146>>>>>>>///
84146>>>>>>>/// @Syntax SQL_AVAILABLE_SQL_SERVER_NAME {index} to {variable}
84146>>>>>>>/// @Param index                The numbered index name to retrieve
84146>>>>>>>/// @Param variable             Variable to hold the server name
84146>>>>>>>///
84146>>>>>>>/// @Example
84146>>>>>>>/// GET_NO_AVAILABLE_SQLSERVERS to iServers
84146>>>>>>>///
84146>>>>>>>/// While (i <= iServers)
84146>>>>>>>///     GET_SQLSERVER_NAME i to sServer
84146>>>>>>>///     Showln sServer
84146>>>>>>>///     Increment i
84146>>>>>>>/// Loop
84146>>>>>>>
84146>>>>>>>Function SQL_AVAILABLE_SQL_SERVER_NAME Global Integer iIndex Returns String
84148>>>>>>>    Local String sName
84148>>>>>>>
84148>>>>>>>    Get MertechInc_Pre_Size_String 80 to sName
84149>>>>>>>    Call_Driver 0 SQLFLEX Function CALLDRV_ENUMERATE_SERVER CALLBACK 0 PASSING sName iIndex CALLDRV_ENUMERATE_SERVER_SERVER RESULT MertechInc_iRet
84154>>>>>>>
84154>>>>>>>    Function_Return sName
84155>>>>>>>End_Function
84156>>>>>>>
84156>>>>>>>
84156>>>>>>>//=============================================================================
84156>>>>>>>/// @Name        SET_USE_ROWCOUNT_IN_TRANSACTION
84156>>>>>>>/// @Description Turn on / off Row_Count for specified server.
84156>>>>>>>/// @Status      Deprecated
84156>>>>>>>/// @Drivers     All
84156>>>>>>>/// @VersionNote Last Revised: 2009-09-21 By Ian Smith
84156>>>>>>>///
84156>>>>>>>/// @Syntax SET_USE_ROWCOUNT_IN_TRANSACTION OF <Server> To <State>
84156>>>>>>>/// @Param Server      Name of server to turn On / Off Row_Count
84156>>>>>>>/// @Param State       TRUE = turn on Row_Count  FALSE = turn off Row_Count
84156>>>>>>>///
84156>>>>>>>/// @Comment This SHOULD ALWAYS BE TURNED ON
84156>>>>>>>
84156>>>>>>>Procedure Set SQL_USE_ROWCOUNT_IN_TRANSACTIONS Global String sServer Integer iState
84158>>>>>>>    DO_GETFILENUMBER_DRIVERNAME 0
84160>>>>>>>
84160>>>>>>>    Call_Driver 0 MertechInc_DriverName Function CALLDRV_USE_ROWCOUNT_IN_TRANSACTIONS CALLBACK 0 PASSING sServer iState CALLDRV_VALUE_SET RESULT MertechInc_iRet
84165>>>>>>>    If MertechInc_iRet EQ -1 INDICATE ERR True
84168>>>>>>>End_Procedure
84169>>>>>>>
84169>>>>>>>//IGS - commented out by a.n. Other
84169>>>>>>>//#REPLACE UseRowCountInTransactions SQL_USE_ROWCOUNT_IN_TRANSACTIONS
84169>>>>>>>
84169>>>>>>>//=============================================================================
84169>>>>>>>/// @Name        GET_USE_ROWCOUNT_IN_TRANSACTION
84169>>>>>>>/// @Description Gets the Row_Count setting for specified server.
84169>>>>>>>/// @Status      Deprecated
84169>>>>>>>/// @Drivers     All
84169>>>>>>>/// @VersionNote Last Revised: 2009-09-21 By Ian Smith
84169>>>>>>>///
84169>>>>>>>/// @Syntax GET_USE_ROWCOUNT_IN_TRANSACTION OF <Server> To <State>
84169>>>>>>>/// @Param Server      Name of server to get Row_Count state of
84169>>>>>>>/// @Param State       Variable to hold returned value
84169>>>>>>>
84169>>>>>>>Function SQL_USE_ROWCOUNT_IN_TRANSACTIONS Global String sServer Returns Integer
84171>>>>>>>    DO_GETFILENUMBER_DRIVERNAME 0
84173>>>>>>>
84173>>>>>>>    Call_Driver 0 MertechInc_DriverName Function CALLDRV_USE_ROWCOUNT_IN_TRANSACTIONS CALLBACK 0 PASSING sServer MertechInc_Blank CALLDRV_VALUE_GET RESULT MertechInc_iRet
84178>>>>>>>
84178>>>>>>>    Function_Return MertechInc_iRet
84179>>>>>>>End_Function
84180>>>>>>>
84180>>>>>>>
84180>>>>>>>//=============================================================================
84180>>>>>>>/// @Name        SQL_SET_DATE_FORMAT
84180>>>>>>>/// @Description This command controls the date format of data returned
84180>>>>>>>/// through embedded SQL. If set to DATAFLEX, then the dates will be
84180>>>>>>>/// returned in whatever format is set in DF_DATE_FORMAT. When set to
84180>>>>>>>/// NATIVE, this command will force dates to return dates in the format
84180>>>>>>>/// specified on the SQL server. Note that in order for the variables to
84180>>>>>>>/// be in the right form, they need to be string variables.
84180>>>>>>>///
84180>>>>>>>/// @Assumptions
84180>>>>>>>/// @Status      Public
84180>>>>>>>/// @Drivers     SQLFlex
84180>>>>>>>/// @VersionNote Last Revised: 2013-10-02 by Aaron Gulack
84180>>>>>>>/// @See
84180>>>>>>>///
84180>>>>>>>/// @Syntax SQL_SET_DATE_FORMAT to {DATAFLEX/NATIVE}
84180>>>>>>>///
84180>>>>>>>/// @Example
84180>>>>>>>/// SQL_SET_DATE_FORMAT to NATIVE
84180>>>>>>>
84180>>>>>>>Procedure Set SQL_USE_DATAFLEX_DATEFORMAT Global Integer iState
84182>>>>>>>    DO_GETFILENUMBER_DRIVERNAME 0
84184>>>>>>>
84184>>>>>>>    If MertechInc_DriverName eq SQLFlex Begin
84186>>>>>>>        Call_Driver 0 MertechInc_DriverName Function CALLDRV_USE_DFLEX_DATE_FORMAT CALLBACK 0 PASSING iState MertechInc_Blank CALLDRV_VALUE_SET RESULT MertechInc_iRet
84191>>>>>>>        IF MertechInc_iRet EQ -1 INDICATE ERR TRUE
84194>>>>>>>    End
84194>>>>>>>>
84194>>>>>>>End_Procedure
84195>>>>>>>
84195>>>>>>>Function SQL_USE_DATAFLEX_DATEFORMAT Global Returns Integer
84197>>>>>>>    DO_GETFILENUMBER_DRIVERNAME 0
84199>>>>>>>
84199>>>>>>>    If MertechInc_DriverName eq SQLFlex Begin
84201>>>>>>>        CALL_DRIVER 0 MertechInc_DriverName FUNCTION CALLDRV_USE_DFLEX_DATE_FORMAT CALLBACK 0 PASSING MertechInc_Blank MertechInc_Blank CALLDRV_VALUE_GET RESULT MertechInc_iRet
84206>>>>>>>    End
84206>>>>>>>>
84206>>>>>>>    Else Move DFFALSE to MertechInc_iRet
84208>>>>>>>
84208>>>>>>>    function_return MertechInc_iRet
84209>>>>>>>End_Function
84210>>>>>>>
84210>>>>>>>
84210>>>>>>>//=============================================================================
84210>>>>>>>/// @Name        SET_FIELDS_NOT_NULL
84210>>>>>>>/// @Description This command is used to specify how to handle blank
84210>>>>>>>/// and zero values on the SQL backend. Since blank or zero values can
84210>>>>>>>/// often be stored as null in the server database, this command allows
84210>>>>>>>/// that to be altered if needed. When set to true, a value will be
84210>>>>>>>/// inserted into blank records to keep them from being null. See the
84210>>>>>>>/// list below for what value will be stored instead of null. If set to
84210>>>>>>>/// false, values will be stored normally in the database. Note that this
84210>>>>>>>/// command effects all data types.
84210>>>>>>>///
84210>>>>>>>/// DF_ASCII and DF_TEXT -              ' ' (one blank space)
84210>>>>>>>///
84210>>>>>>>/// DF_BCD -                                    0 (zero)
84210>>>>>>>///
84210>>>>>>>/// DF_DATe and DF_DATETIME -   00/00/0000 for MYSQL
84210>>>>>>>///                                                             01/01/0001 for Oracle MSSQL, and Postgre
84210>>>>>>>///                                                             01/01/1753 for MSSQL Datetimes
84210>>>>>>>///
84210>>>>>>>/// DF_BINARY -                                 0X0
84210>>>>>>>///
84210>>>>>>>/// @Assumptions
84210>>>>>>>/// @Status      Public
84210>>>>>>>/// @Drivers     All
84210>>>>>>>/// @VersionNote Last Revised: 2013-10-08 by Aaron Gulack
84210>>>>>>>/// @See                 SET_FIELDS_NULL GET_FIELDS_NULL
84210>>>>>>>///
84210>>>>>>>/// @Syntax SET_FIELDS_NOT_NULL to {variable}
84210>>>>>>>/// @Param variable             Boolean variable to indicate how to handle null values
84210>>>>>>>///
84210>>>>>>>
84210>>>>>>>Procedure Set SQL_FORCE_FIELDS_NOT_NULL Global Integer iState
84212>>>>>>>    DO_GETFILENUMBER_DRIVERNAME 0
84214>>>>>>>
84214>>>>>>>    If (MertechInc_FileNumber <> -1) Begin
84216>>>>>>>        Call_Driver 0 MertechInc_DriverName Function CALLDRV_FORCE_FIELDS_NOT_NULL CALLBACK 0 PASSING iState MertechInc_Blank CALLDRV_VALUE_SET RESULT MertechInc_iRet
84221>>>>>>>        If MertechInc_iRet EQ -1 INDICATE ERR True
84224>>>>>>>    End
84224>>>>>>>>
84224>>>>>>>End_Procedure
84225>>>>>>>
84225>>>>>>>
84225>>>>>>>
84225>>>>>>>
84225>>>>>>>Function SQL_FORCE_FIELDS_NOT_NULL Global Returns Integer
84227>>>>>>>    DO_GETFILENUMBER_DRIVERNAME 0
84229>>>>>>>
84229>>>>>>>    If (MertechInc_FileNumber <> -1) Begin
84231>>>>>>>        Call_Driver 0 MertechInc_DriverName Function CALLDRV_FORCE_FIELDS_NOT_NULL CALLBACK 0 PASSING MertechInc_Blank MertechInc_Blank CALLDRV_VALUE_GET RESULT MertechInc_iRet
84236>>>>>>>    End
84236>>>>>>>>
84236>>>>>>>    Else Move DFFALSE to MertechInc_iRet
84238>>>>>>>
84238>>>>>>>    Function_Return MertechInc_iRet
84239>>>>>>>End_Function
84240>>>>>>>
84240>>>>>>>
84240>>>>>>>//=============================================================================
84240>>>>>>>/// @Name        SET_FIELDS_NULL
84240>>>>>>>/// @Description This command is used to specify how to store blank or zero
84240>>>>>>>/// values in the database. Since database can sometimes store these value,
84240>>>>>>>/// i.e. '' or 0, as null, using this command can be useful in managing that.
84240>>>>>>>/// When set to true, any value in a column of the given type considered blank
84240>>>>>>>/// or 0 will be stored as null in the database. Setting it to false will cause
84240>>>>>>>/// the server to save as it normally would. Note that this command is used to
84240>>>>>>>/// set specific data types only, it can not effect all types at once. Below is
84240>>>>>>>/// a list of value that would be considered blank/zero values.
84240>>>>>>>///
84240>>>>>>>/// DF_ASCII and DF_TEXT -              ' ' (one blank space)
84240>>>>>>>///
84240>>>>>>>/// DF_BCD -                                    0 (zero)
84240>>>>>>>///
84240>>>>>>>/// DF_DATe and DF_DATETIME -   00/00/0000 for MYSQL
84240>>>>>>>///                                                             01/01/0001 for Oracle MSSQL, and Postgre
84240>>>>>>>///                                                             01/01/1753 for MSSQL Datetimes
84240>>>>>>>///
84240>>>>>>>/// DF_BINARY -                                 0X0
84240>>>>>>>///
84240>>>>>>>/// @Assumptions
84240>>>>>>>/// @Status      Public
84240>>>>>>>/// @Drivers     All
84240>>>>>>>/// @VersionNote Last Revised: 2013-10-08 by Aaron Gulack
84240>>>>>>>/// @See                 GET_FIELDS_NULL SET_FIELDS_NOT_NULL
84240>>>>>>>///
84240>>>>>>>/// @Syntax SET_FIELDS_NULL {datatype} to {variable}
84240>>>>>>>/// @Param datatype                     DF_ASCII, DF_BCD, or DF_DATE
84240>>>>>>>/// @Param variable             Boolean to indicate how to handle blank data
84240>>>>>>>
84240>>>>>>>
84240>>>>>>>//=============================================================================
84240>>>>>>>/// @Name        GET_FIELDS_NULL
84240>>>>>>>/// @Description This command will return the value of SET_FIELDS_NULL for
84240>>>>>>>/// the specified data type.
84240>>>>>>>///
84240>>>>>>>/// @Assumptions
84240>>>>>>>/// @Status      Public
84240>>>>>>>/// @Drivers     All
84240>>>>>>>/// @VersionNote Last Revised: 2013-10-08 by Aaron Gulack
84240>>>>>>>/// @See                 SET_FIELDS_NULL SET_FIELDS_NOT_NULL
84240>>>>>>>///
84240>>>>>>>/// @Syntax GET_FIELDS_NULL {datatype} to {variable}
84240>>>>>>>/// @Param datatype                     DF_ASCII, DF_BCD, or DF_DATE
84240>>>>>>>/// @Param variable             Variable to hold the value of SET_FIELDS_NULL
84240>>>>>>>
84240>>>>>>>
84240>>>>>>>//=============================================================================
84240>>>>>>>/// @Name        STRUCTURE_START_DYNAMIC
84240>>>>>>>/// @Description This command is used when scripting structural changes.
84240>>>>>>>/// It is the same as using ENABLE_SCRIPTING and Structure_Start separately.
84240>>>>>>>/// It allows structural changes to be compiled and tested without
84240>>>>>>>/// actually making any of the changes. Any table restructuring done
84240>>>>>>>/// between this command and STRUCTURE_END_DYNAMIC will not actually be
84240>>>>>>>/// committed but will instead create a mock INT file. The script and
84240>>>>>>>/// INT file can then be retrieved and examined for testing purposes.
84240>>>>>>>///
84240>>>>>>>/// @Assumptions
84240>>>>>>>/// @Status      Deprecated
84240>>>>>>>/// @Drivers     All
84240>>>>>>>/// @VersionNote Last Revised: 2013-10-09 by Aaron Gulack
84240>>>>>>>/// @See                 ENABLE_SCRIPTING DISABLE_SCRIPTING
84240>>>>>>>///
84240>>>>>>>/// @Syntax STRUCTURE_START_DYNAMIC of {FileNumber}
84240>>>>>>>/// @Param FileNumber                   The number of the file
84240>>>>>>>
84240>>>>>>>//=============================================================================
84240>>>>>>>/// @Name        STRUCTURE_END_DYNAMIC
84240>>>>>>>/// @Description This command ends the scripting started by
84240>>>>>>>/// STRUCTURE_START_DYNAMIC. It is the same as calling Structure_End
84240>>>>>>>/// and DISABLE_SCRIPTING separately.
84240>>>>>>>///
84240>>>>>>>/// @Assumptions
84240>>>>>>>/// @Status      Deprecated
84240>>>>>>>/// @Drivers     All
84240>>>>>>>/// @VersionNote Last Revised: 2013-10-09 by Aaron Gulack
84240>>>>>>>/// @See                 ENABLE_SCRIPTING DISABLE_SCRIPTING
84240>>>>>>>///
84240>>>>>>>/// @Syntax STRUCTURE_START_DYNAMIC of {FileNumber}
84240>>>>>>>/// @Param FileNumber                   The number of the file
84240>>>>>>>
84240>>>>>>>//=============================================================================
84240>>>>>>>/// @Name        SQLSERVER_ATTACH_DB
84240>>>>>>>/// @Description Attachs an MS SQL mdf to the current server instance. If
84240>>>>>>>/// the passed database is already attached, no error is generated.
84240>>>>>>>///
84240>>>>>>>/// The SQLSERVER_ATTACH_DB command is intended for use with our new support
84240>>>>>>>/// of Microsoft LocalDB's.  When using LocalDB's a common use case might be
84240>>>>>>>/// to attach to a customer DB, do some work on it, and then detach this DB
84240>>>>>>>/// and attach to a different DB.  This was possible using stored procedures,
84240>>>>>>>/// but the code had some complexities that a developer need not worry about.
84240>>>>>>>/// When you attach a database, you must pass the database name, along with
84240>>>>>>>/// the path to an MDF file which contains the database.  Any associated LDF's
84240>>>>>>>/// (log files) and NDF's (secondary data files) must be in the same folder.
84240>>>>>>>///
84240>>>>>>>/// If you call SQLSERVER_ATTACH_DB on a database that is already attached,
84240>>>>>>>/// no error will be generated.  After you call SQLSERVER_ATTACH_DB, you
84240>>>>>>>/// should call SET_DATABASE_NAME if you wish to make the attached database
84240>>>>>>>/// the currently selected database.
84240>>>>>>>///
84240>>>>>>>/// SQLSERVER_ATTACH_DB will work on all supported version of SQL server.
84240>>>>>>>///
84240>>>>>>>/// @Assumptions
84240>>>>>>>/// @Status      Public
84240>>>>>>>/// @Drivers     SQLFlex
84240>>>>>>>/// @VersionNote Last Revised: 2013-10-09 Aaron Gulack
84240>>>>>>>/// @See
84240>>>>>>>///
84240>>>>>>>/// @Syntax SQLSERVER_ATTACH_DB {database} on {filePath}
84240>>>>>>>/// @Param database                     Name of the database
84240>>>>>>>/// @Param filePath                     Path of the MDF file
84240>>>>>>>///
84240>>>>>>>/// @Example
84240>>>>>>>/// SQLSERVER_ATTACH_DB "MTSample" ON "C:\Mertech\Data\SampleDb.mdf"
84240>>>>>>>
84240>>>>>>>//=============================================================================
84240>>>>>>>/// @Name        SQLSERVER_DETACH_DB
84240>>>>>>>/// @Description The SQLSERVER_DETACH_DB command is intended for use with our
84240>>>>>>>/// new support of Microsoft LocalDB's.  When using LocalDB's a common use
84240>>>>>>>/// case might be to attach to a customer DB, do some work on it, and then
84240>>>>>>>/// detach this DB and attach to a different DB.  This was possible using
84240>>>>>>>/// stored procedures, but the code had some complexities that a developer
84240>>>>>>>/// need not worry about.  A detach can only be done if the database passed
84240>>>>>>>/// has no open connections.  As part of the detach process, the command
84240>>>>>>>/// closes ALL open files (even those not associated with this database or
84240>>>>>>>/// driver).
84240>>>>>>>///
84240>>>>>>>/// NOTE: SQLSERVER_DETACH_DB will often fail to execute if you are testing
84240>>>>>>>/// your application from the studio.  This is because the studio itself
84240>>>>>>>/// normally has open connections to the database.  If you test your
84240>>>>>>>/// application outside of the studio and the studio is closed (and any
84240>>>>>>>/// other application or tools that access this database are closed) you
84240>>>>>>>/// can successfully detach the database.
84240>>>>>>>///
84240>>>>>>>/// @Assumptions
84240>>>>>>>/// @Status      Public
84240>>>>>>>/// @Drivers     SQLFlex
84240>>>>>>>/// @VersionNote Last Revised: 2013-10-09 by Aaron Gulack
84240>>>>>>>/// @See
84240>>>>>>>///
84240>>>>>>>/// @Syntax SQLSERVER_DETACH_DB {database}
84240>>>>>>>/// @Param database                     Name of the database
84240>>>>>>>///
84240>>>>>>>/// @Example
84240>>>>>>>/// SQLSERVER_DETACH_DB "TestDB"
84240>>>>>>>
84240>>>>>>>//=============================================================================
84240>>>>>>>/// @Name        SET_FIXED_FILE_RECORDS_USED
84240>>>>>>>/// @Description This command is used to set DF_FILE_RECORDS_USED to a
84240>>>>>>>/// fixed value. This can be useful because doing a SELECT COUNT(*) is
84240>>>>>>>/// a very expensive process to the server. Many applications do counts
84240>>>>>>>/// often and using this command can help cut down the server traffic.
84240>>>>>>>/// Sometimes when counts are used, an exact number is not necessary so
84240>>>>>>>/// a fixed value, updated occasionally can be used. By setting this
84240>>>>>>>/// command to 0 or greater, the value of DF_FILE_RECORDS_USED will be
84240>>>>>>>/// set to that specified value and the internal SELECT COUNT(*) will be
84240>>>>>>>/// suppressed. If this command is set to something less that zero,
84240>>>>>>>/// DF_FILE_RECORDS_USED will be dynamically calculated whenever it is
84240>>>>>>>/// called.
84240>>>>>>>///
84240>>>>>>>/// The default value for this command is -1
84240>>>>>>>///
84240>>>>>>>/// @Assumptions
84240>>>>>>>/// @Status              Public
84240>>>>>>>/// @Drivers     All
84240>>>>>>>/// @VersionNote Last Revised: 2013-10-09 by Aaron Gulack
84240>>>>>>>/// @See                 GET_FIXED_FILE_RECORDS_USED SUPPRESS_SELECT_COUNT UNSUPPRESS_SELECT_COUNT
84240>>>>>>>///
84240>>>>>>>/// @Syntax SET_FIXED_FILE_RECORDS_USED to {variable}
84240>>>>>>>/// @Param variable                     Fixed value for DF_FILE_RECORDS_USED
84240>>>>>>>///
84240>>>>>>>/// @Example
84240>>>>>>>/// SET_FIXED_FILE_RECORDS_USED to 10000
84240>>>>>>>
84240>>>>>>>//=============================================================================
84240>>>>>>>/// @Name        GET_FIXED_FILE_RECORDS_USED
84240>>>>>>>/// @Description This command returns the value of DF_FILE_RECORDS_USED
84240>>>>>>>/// if it has been set to a fixed value by SET_FIXED_FILE_RECORDS_USED.
84240>>>>>>>/// If anything greater than or equal to 0 is returned then that is the
84240>>>>>>>/// fixed value returned by any SELECT COUNT(*) statements, internal or
84240>>>>>>>/// not. If something less than zero is returned, then DF_FILE_RECORDS_USED
84240>>>>>>>/// returns a dynamic count whenever it is called.
84240>>>>>>>///
84240>>>>>>>/// By default the value of this is -1
84240>>>>>>>///
84240>>>>>>>/// @Assumptions
84240>>>>>>>/// @Status              Public
84240>>>>>>>/// @Drivers     All
84240>>>>>>>/// @VersionNote Last Revised: 2013-10-09 by Aaron Gulack
84240>>>>>>>/// @See                 SET_FIXED_FILE_RECORDS_USED SUPPRESS_SELECT_COUNT UNSUPPRESS_SELECT_COUNT
84240>>>>>>>///
84240>>>>>>>/// @Syntax GET_FILE_RECORDS_USED to {variable}
84240>>>>>>>/// @Param variable                     Variable to hold the fixed value
84240>>>>>>>///
84240>>>>>>>/// @Example
84240>>>>>>>/// GET_FIXED_FILE_RECORDS_USED to iRecords
84240>>>>>>>
84240>>>>>>>//=============================================================================
84240>>>>>>>/// @Name        SUPPRESS_SELECT_COUNT
84240>>>>>>>/// @Description This command sets the value of DF_FILE_RECORDS_USED to
84240>>>>>>>/// a fixed value of zero. That way anytime a SELECT COUNT(*) is done,
84240>>>>>>>/// zero is returned, cutting down on server traffic. This is the same
84240>>>>>>>/// as setting SET_FIXED_FILE_RECORDS_USED to 0.
84240>>>>>>>///
84240>>>>>>>/// @Assumptions
84240>>>>>>>/// @Status      Public
84240>>>>>>>/// @Drivers     All
84240>>>>>>>/// @VersionNote Last Revised: 2013-10-09 by Aaron Gulack
84240>>>>>>>/// @See                 UNSUPPRESS_SELECT_COUNT SET_FIXED_FILE_RECORDS_USED GET_FIXED_FILE_RECORDS_USED
84240>>>>>>>///
84240>>>>>>>/// @Syntax SUPPRESS_SELECT_COUNT
84240>>>>>>>
84240>>>>>>>//=============================================================================
84240>>>>>>>/// @Name        UNSUPPRESS_SELECT_COUNT
84240>>>>>>>/// @Description This command resets the value of DF_FILE_RECORDS_USED to
84240>>>>>>>/// -1. That way anytime a SELECT COUNT(*) is done, it returns the actual
84240>>>>>>>/// count of records. This is the same as setting SET_FIXED_FILE_RECORDS_USED
84240>>>>>>>/// to -1.
84240>>>>>>>///
84240>>>>>>>/// @Assumptions
84240>>>>>>>/// @Status      Public
84240>>>>>>>/// @Drivers     All
84240>>>>>>>/// @VersionNote Last Revised: 2013-10-09 by Aaron Gulack
84240>>>>>>>/// @See                 SUPPRESS_SELECT_COUNT SET_FIXED_FILE_RECORDS_USED GET_FIXED_FILE_RECORDS_USED
84240>>>>>>>///
84240>>>>>>>/// @Syntax UNSUPPRESS_SELECT_COUNT
84240>>>>>>>
84240>>>>>>>
84240>>>>>>>///
84240>>>>>>>// Private:
84240>>>>>>>// Get the filenumber of a file.field parameter
84240>>>>>>>//
84240>>>>>>>
84240>>>>>>>///
84240>>>>>>>// Private:
84240>>>>>>>// Get the fieldnumber of a file.field parameter
84240>>>>>>>//
84240>>>>>>>
84240>>>>>>>
84240>>>>>>>
84240>>>>>>>
84240>>>>>>>//
84240>>>>>>>// Minimum required DataFlex version for new LOB support below is VDF 4
84240>>>>>>>//
84240>>>>>>>
84240>>>>>>>TYPE tMertechLOB_Args
84240>>>>>>>    FIELD tMertechLOB_Args.cbSize       AS WORD          // always the size of the structure (verification + versioning)
84240>>>>>>>    FIELD tMertechLOB_Args.nField       AS DWORD         // always the field number
84240>>>>>>>    FIELD tMertechLOB_Args.pszData      AS POINTER
84240>>>>>>>    FIELD tMertechLOB_Args.nSize        AS DWORD
84240>>>>>>>    FIELD tMertechLOB_Args.nOffset      AS POINTER
84240>>>>>>>END_TYPE
84240>>>>>>>
84240>>>>>>>//=============================================================================
84240>>>>>>>/// @Name        SQL_SET_LOB
84240>>>>>>>/// @Description This command replaces whatever is currently in a LOB Field
84240>>>>>>>/// with the data passed. It writes to a client side buffer. It can be used
84240>>>>>>>/// to Write an arbitrary amount of data into a LOB.
84240>>>>>>>/// If passed an empty String, it will remove all the contents of the LOB.
84240>>>>>>>/// If you wish to Set a LOB back to NULL, please use the SQL_SET_LOB_NULL
84240>>>>>>>/// command.
84240>>>>>>>/// NOTE: Unlike the previous call LOB_WRITE, this call does not
84240>>>>>>>/// perform the Save. This must be done separately.
84240>>>>>>>///
84240>>>>>>>/// @Assumptions The field being used is a LOB field
84240>>>>>>>/// @Status      Public
84240>>>>>>>/// @Drivers     All
84240>>>>>>>/// @VersionNote Last Revised: 2014-07-10 by Aaron Gulack
84240>>>>>>>/// @See                 SQL_ADD_LOB_CHUNK SQL_GET_LOB SQL_GET_LOB_CHUNK SQL_GET_LOB_LENGTH SQL_LOB_TRUNCATE
84240>>>>>>>///
84240>>>>>>>/// @Syntax             SQL_SET_LOB {FileName.FieldName} to {variable}
84240>>>>>>>/// @Param              FileName                The name of the file containing the LOB field
84240>>>>>>>/// @Param              FieldName               The name of the LOB field being set
84240>>>>>>>/// @Param              variable                The variable to use to set the field's value
84240>>>>>>>///
84240>>>>>>>/// @Example
84240>>>>>>>/// Set_Argument_Size 262144
84240>>>>>>>/// String sLine
84240>>>>>>>///
84240>>>>>>>/// Clear Customer
84240>>>>>>>///    Move iID to Customer.ID
84240>>>>>>>/// Find Eq Customer by Index.1
84240>>>>>>>/// If (Found) Begin
84240>>>>>>>///    Direct_Input "C:\bigFile.xml"
84240>>>>>>>///    Reread Customer
84240>>>>>>>///       SQL_SET_LOB Customer.Comments to ""
84240>>>>>>>///       Read_Block sLine 262144
84240>>>>>>>///       SQL_SET_LOB Customer.Comments to sLine
84240>>>>>>>///       While (not(SeqEof))
84240>>>>>>>///          Read_Block sLine 262144
84240>>>>>>>///          SQL_ADD_LOB_CHUNK Customer.Comments to sLine
84240>>>>>>>///       Loop
84240>>>>>>>///    Saverecord Customer
84240>>>>>>>///    Unlock
84240>>>>>>>///    Close_Input
84240>>>>>>>/// End
84240>>>>>>>
84240>>>>>>>Procedure MertechInc_SQL_SET_LOB String sDriver Integer iFile Integer iField String sData
84243>>>>>>>    Local String sLOB_Args       // can drop local command if minimum vdf version is 6
84243>>>>>>>
84243>>>>>>>    ZeroType tMertechLOB_Args to sLOB_Args
84244>>>>>>>    // First move the size of the structure to the Structure
84244>>>>>>>    Put tMertechLOB_Args_size to sLOB_Args at tMertechLOB_Args.cbSize
84245>>>>>>>    Put iField                to sLOB_Args at tMertechLOB_Args.nField
84246>>>>>>>    Put (AddressOf(sData))    to sLOB_Args at tMertechLOB_Args.pszData
84247>>>>>>>    Put (length(sData))       to sLOB_Args at tMertechLOB_Args.nSize
84248>>>>>>>
84248>>>>>>>    Call_Driver iFile sDriver Function CALLDRV_LOB_EX_WRITE CALLBACK 0 PASSING MertechInc_Blank MertechInc_Blank (addressof(sLOB_Args)) RESULT MertechInc_iRet
84253>>>>>>>End_Procedure // MertechInc_SQL_SET_LOB
84254>>>>>>>
84254>>>>>>>//=============================================================================
84254>>>>>>>/// @Name        SQL_ADD_LOB_CHUNK
84254>>>>>>>/// @Description This command is used to add additional chunks to the buffer
84254>>>>>>>/// before saving the record. After SQL_SET_LOB has been called
84254>>>>>>>/// SQL_ADD_LOB_CHUNK can be called as many times as needed to add additional
84254>>>>>>>/// chunks of data before a save. It can also be called independent of
84254>>>>>>>/// SQL_SET_LOB to append data to an existing LOB column.
84254>>>>>>>/// NOTE: Unlike the previous call LOB_APPEND, this call does not perform
84254>>>>>>>/// the save. This must be done separately.
84254>>>>>>>///
84254>>>>>>>/// @Assumptions The field being used is a LOB field
84254>>>>>>>/// @Status      Public
84254>>>>>>>/// @Drivers     All
84254>>>>>>>/// @VersionNote Last Revised: 2014-07-10 by Aaron Gulack
84254>>>>>>>/// @See                 SQL_SET_LOB SQL_GET_LOB SQL_GET_LOB_CHUNK SQL_GET_LOB_LENGTH SQL_LOB_TRUNCATE
84254>>>>>>>///
84254>>>>>>>/// @Syntax             SQL_ADD_LOB_CHUNK {FileName.FieldName} to {variable}
84254>>>>>>>/// @Param              FileName                The name of the file containing the LOB field
84254>>>>>>>/// @Param              FieldName               The name of the LOB field being set
84254>>>>>>>/// @Param              variable                The variable to add as the LOB chunk
84254>>>>>>>///
84254>>>>>>>/// @Example
84254>>>>>>>/// Set_Argument_Size 262144
84254>>>>>>>/// String sLine
84254>>>>>>>///
84254>>>>>>>/// Clear Customer
84254>>>>>>>///    Move iID to Customer.ID
84254>>>>>>>/// Find Eq Customer by Index.1
84254>>>>>>>/// If (Found) Begin
84254>>>>>>>///    Direct_Input "C:\bigFile.xml"
84254>>>>>>>///    Reread Customer
84254>>>>>>>///       SQL_SET_LOB Customer.Comments to ""
84254>>>>>>>///       Read_Block sLine 262144
84254>>>>>>>///       SQL_SET_LOB Customer.Comments to sLine
84254>>>>>>>///       While (not(SeqEof))
84254>>>>>>>///          Read_Block sLine 262144
84254>>>>>>>///          SQL_ADD_LOB_CHUNK Customer.Comments to sLine
84254>>>>>>>///       Loop
84254>>>>>>>///    Saverecord Customer
84254>>>>>>>///    Unlock
84254>>>>>>>///    Close_Input
84254>>>>>>>/// End
84254>>>>>>>
84254>>>>>>>Procedure MertechInc_SQL_ADD_LOB_CHUNK String sDriver Integer iFile Integer iField String sData
84257>>>>>>>    Local String sLOB_Args
84257>>>>>>>
84257>>>>>>>    ZeroType tMertechLOB_Args to sLOB_Args
84258>>>>>>>    // First move the size of the structure to the Structure
84258>>>>>>>    Put tMertechLOB_Args_size to sLOB_Args at tMertechLOB_Args.cbSize
84259>>>>>>>    Put iField                to sLOB_Args at tMertechLOB_Args.nField
84260>>>>>>>    Put (AddressOf(sData))    to sLOB_Args at tMertechLOB_Args.pszData
84261>>>>>>>    Put (length(sData))       to sLOB_Args at tMertechLOB_Args.nSize
84262>>>>>>>
84262>>>>>>>    Call_Driver iFile sDriver Function CALLDRV_LOB_EX_APPEND CALLBACK 0 PASSING MertechInc_Blank MertechInc_Blank (addressof(sLOB_Args)) RESULT MertechInc_iRet
84267>>>>>>>end_procedure // MertechInc_SQL_ADD_LOB_CHUNK
84268>>>>>>>
84268>>>>>>>//=============================================================================
84268>>>>>>>/// @Name        SQL_GET_LOB
84268>>>>>>>/// @Description This command is used for getting the value of a specified LOB
84268>>>>>>>/// field. Two optional parameters can be passed specifying the offset and
84268>>>>>>>/// length of the chunk to get. Passing these parameters essentially makes this
84268>>>>>>>/// call the same as SQL_GET_LOB_CHUNK.
84268>>>>>>>/// Depending on the situation, the two calls can be interchanged for improved
84268>>>>>>>/// code readability. Excluding these additional parameters will get the whole
84268>>>>>>>/// field value within DataFlex variable size limits.
84268>>>>>>>///
84268>>>>>>>/// @Assumptions The field being used is a LOB field
84268>>>>>>>/// @Status      Public
84268>>>>>>>/// @Drivers     All
84268>>>>>>>/// @VersionNote Last Revised: 2014-07-10 by Aaron Gulack
84268>>>>>>>/// @See                 SQL_SET_LOB SQL_ADD_LOB_CHUNK SQL_GET_LOB_CHUNK SQL_GET_LOB_LENGTH SQL_LOB_TRUNCATE
84268>>>>>>>///
84268>>>>>>>/// @Syntax     SQL_GET_LOB {FileName.FieldName} TO {variable} [ OFFSET {offset} LENGTH {length} ]
84268>>>>>>>/// @Param              FileName                        The name of the file that contains the specified LOB field
84268>>>>>>>/// @Param              FieldName                       The name of the LOB field
84268>>>>>>>/// @Param              variable                        The variable to hold the LOB value
84268>>>>>>>/// @Param              offset                          Integer amount to offset when getting the LOB value (optional)
84268>>>>>>>/// @Param              length                          Length of value to get from the LOB field (optional)
84268>>>>>>>///
84268>>>>>>>/// @Example
84268>>>>>>>/// Set_Argument_Size 262144
84268>>>>>>>/// String sResult
84268>>>>>>>///
84268>>>>>>>/// Move 262144 to iChunkSize
84268>>>>>>>/// Move 0      to iChunk
84268>>>>>>>///
84268>>>>>>>/// Clear Customer
84268>>>>>>>///    Move iID to Customer.ID
84268>>>>>>>/// Find Eq Customer by Index.1
84268>>>>>>>/// If (Found) Begin
84268>>>>>>>///    Direct_Output ('Binary:' + sDestFileName)
84268>>>>>>>///    SQL_GET_LOB_LENGTH Customer.Comments to iLength
84268>>>>>>>///    While (iChunk*iChunkSize < iLength)
84268>>>>>>>///       SQL_GET_LOB Customer.Comments to sResult OFFSET (iChunk*iChunkSize) LENGTH iChunkSize
84268>>>>>>>///       Write sResult
84268>>>>>>>///       Increment iChunk
84268>>>>>>>///    Loop
84268>>>>>>>///    Close_Output
84268>>>>>>>/// End
84268>>>>>>>
84268>>>>>>>
84268>>>>>>>Function MertechInc_SQL_GET_LOB String sDriver Integer iFile Integer iField Integer iOffset Integer iLength Returns String
84271>>>>>>>    Local String sLOB_Args
84271>>>>>>>    Local String sData
84271>>>>>>>    Local DWord  nSize
84271>>>>>>>
84271>>>>>>>    Move "" To sData
84272>>>>>>>    ZeroType tMertechLOB_Args to sLOB_Args
84273>>>>>>>    // First move the size of the structure to the Structure
84273>>>>>>>    Put tMertechLOB_Args_size to sLOB_Args at tMertechLOB_Args.cbSize
84274>>>>>>>    Put iField                to sLOB_Args at tMertechLOB_Args.nField
84275>>>>>>>
84275>>>>>>>    Call_Driver iFile sDriver Function CALLDRV_LOB_EX_GET_LENGTH CALLBACK 0 PASSING MertechInc_Blank MertechInc_Blank (addressof(sLOB_Args)) RESULT MertechInc_iRet
84280>>>>>>>
84280>>>>>>>    GetBuff from sLOB_Args at tMertechLOB_Args.nSize to nSize
84281>>>>>>>    If nSize GT 0 Begin
84283>>>>>>>      If (iOffset=0 and iLength=0) Begin
84285>>>>>>>        ZeroString nSize to sData
84286>>>>>>>            //Send Assert (AddressOf(sData) <> 0) ("AddressOf(sData) is NULL") DFTrue
84286>>>>>>>        Put (AddressOf(sData)) to sLOB_Args at tMertechLOB_Args.pszData
84287>>>>>>>      End
84287>>>>>>>>
84287>>>>>>>      Else Begin
84288>>>>>>>        ZeroString iLength to sData
84289>>>>>>>        Put (AddressOf(sData)) to sLOB_Args at tMertechLOB_Args.pszData
84290>>>>>>>        Put iLength            to sLOB_Args at tMertechLOB_Args.nSize
84291>>>>>>>        Put iOffset            to sLOB_Args at tMertechLOB_Args.nOffset
84292>>>>>>>      End
84292>>>>>>>>
84292>>>>>>>      Call_Driver iFile sDriver Function CALLDRV_LOB_EX_READ CALLBACK 0 PASSING MertechInc_Blank MertechInc_Blank (addressof(sLOB_Args)) RESULT MertechInc_iRet
84297>>>>>>>    End
84297>>>>>>>>
84297>>>>>>>    Else Begin
84298>>>>>>>        Move "" to sData
84299>>>>>>>    End
84299>>>>>>>>
84299>>>>>>>    Function_Return sData
84300>>>>>>>End_Function // MertechInc_SQL_GET_LOB
84301>>>>>>>
84301>>>>>>>//=============================================================================
84301>>>>>>>/// @Name        SQL_GET_LOB_CHUNK
84301>>>>>>>/// @Description This command is used for getting a chunk of data from a specified
84301>>>>>>>/// LOB field. The difference between this command and SQL_GET_LOB is only that
84301>>>>>>>/// the parameters OFFSET and LENGTH are not optional when using this command.
84301>>>>>>>/// You may consider using this command to retrieve small portions of a very
84301>>>>>>>/// large BLOB so as to reduce memory usage.
84301>>>>>>>///
84301>>>>>>>/// @Assumptions The field being used is a LOB field
84301>>>>>>>/// @Status      Public
84301>>>>>>>/// @Drivers     All
84301>>>>>>>/// @VersionNote Last Revised: 2014-07-10 by Aaron Gulack
84301>>>>>>>/// @See                 SQL_SET_LOB SQL_ADD_LOB_CHUNK SQL_GET_LOB SQL_GET_LOB_LENGTH SQL_LOB_TRUNCATE
84301>>>>>>>///
84301>>>>>>>/// @Syntax     SQL_GET_LOB_CHUNK {FileName.FieldName} TO {variable} OFFSET {offset} LENGTH {length}
84301>>>>>>>/// @Param              FileName                        The name of the file that contains the specified LOB field
84301>>>>>>>/// @Param              FieldName                       The name of the LOB field
84301>>>>>>>/// @Param              variable                        The variable to hold the LOB chunk
84301>>>>>>>/// @Param              offset                          Integer amount to offset when getting the LOB chunk
84301>>>>>>>/// @Param              length                          Length of chunk to get from the LOB field
84301>>>>>>>///
84301>>>>>>>/// @Example
84301>>>>>>>/// Set_Argument_Size 262144
84301>>>>>>>/// String sResult
84301>>>>>>>///
84301>>>>>>>/// Move 262144 to iChunkSize
84301>>>>>>>/// Move 0      to iChunk
84301>>>>>>>///
84301>>>>>>>/// Clear Customer
84301>>>>>>>///    Move iID to Customer.ID
84301>>>>>>>/// Find Eq Customer by Index.1
84301>>>>>>>/// If (Found) Begin
84301>>>>>>>///    SQL_GET_LOB_LENGTH Customer.Comments to iLength
84301>>>>>>>///    While (iChunk*iChunkSize < iLength)
84301>>>>>>>///       SQL_GET_LOB_CHUNK Customer.Comments to sResult OFFSET (iChunk*iChunkSize) LENGTH iChunkSize
84301>>>>>>>///       // Do something with the LOB data
84301>>>>>>>///       Increment iChunk
84301>>>>>>>///    Loop
84301>>>>>>>/// End
84301>>>>>>>
84301>>>>>>>//=============================================================================
84301>>>>>>>/// @Name        SQL_GET_LOB_LENGTH
84301>>>>>>>/// @Description This command is used to get the length of a specified LOB field.
84301>>>>>>>/// It is useful, for example, in determining the number of iterations to
84301>>>>>>>/// perform while reading from a LOB field using chunking.
84301>>>>>>>///
84301>>>>>>>/// @Assumptions The field being used is a LOB field
84301>>>>>>>/// @Status      Public
84301>>>>>>>/// @Drivers     All
84301>>>>>>>/// @VersionNote Last Revised: 2014-07-10 by Aaron Gulack
84301>>>>>>>/// @See                 SQL_SET_LOB SQL_ADD_LOB_CHUNK SQL_GET_LOB SQL_GET_LOB_CHUNK SQL_LOB_TRUNCATE
84301>>>>>>>///
84301>>>>>>>/// @Syntax             SQL_GET_LOB_LENGTH {FileName.FieldName} to {variable}
84301>>>>>>>/// @Param              FileName                        The name of the file containing the LOB field
84301>>>>>>>/// @Param              FieldName                       The name of the specified LOB field
84301>>>>>>>/// @Param              variable                        The variable to hold the length of the field
84301>>>>>>>///
84301>>>>>>>/// @Example
84301>>>>>>>/// Set_Argument_Size 262144
84301>>>>>>>/// String sResult
84301>>>>>>>///
84301>>>>>>>/// Move 16384 to iChunkSize
84301>>>>>>>/// Move 0     to iChunk
84301>>>>>>>///
84301>>>>>>>/// Clear Customer
84301>>>>>>>///    Move iID to Customer.ID
84301>>>>>>>/// Find Eq Customer by Index.1
84301>>>>>>>/// If (Found) Begin
84301>>>>>>>///    SQL_GET_LOB_LENGTH Customer.Comments to iLength
84301>>>>>>>///    While (iChunk*iChunkSize < iLength)
84301>>>>>>>///       SQL_GET_LOB Customer.Comments to sResult OFFSET (iChunk*iChunkSize) LENGTH iChunkSize
84301>>>>>>>///       // Do something with the LOB data
84301>>>>>>>///       Increment iChunk
84301>>>>>>>///    Loop
84301>>>>>>>/// End
84301>>>>>>>
84301>>>>>>>
84301>>>>>>>Function MertechInc_SQL_GET_LOB_LENGTH String sDriver Integer iFile Integer iField Returns Integer
84304>>>>>>>    Local String sLOB_Args
84304>>>>>>>    Local DWord  nSize
84304>>>>>>>
84304>>>>>>>    ZeroType tMertechLOB_Args to sLOB_Args
84305>>>>>>>    // First move the size of the structure to the Structure
84305>>>>>>>    Put tMertechLOB_Args_size to sLOB_Args at tMertechLOB_Args.cbSize
84306>>>>>>>    Put iField                to sLOB_Args at tMertechLOB_Args.nField
84307>>>>>>>
84307>>>>>>>    Call_Driver iFile sDriver Function CALLDRV_LOB_EX_GET_LENGTH CALLBACK 0 PASSING MertechInc_Blank MertechInc_Blank (addressof(sLOB_Args)) RESULT MertechInc_iRet
84312>>>>>>>
84312>>>>>>>    GetBuff from sLOB_Args at tMertechLOB_Args.nSize to nSize
84313>>>>>>>    Function_Return nSize
84314>>>>>>>End_Function // MertechInc_SQL_GET_LOB_LENGTH
84315>>>>>>>
84315>>>>>>>//=============================================================================
84315>>>>>>>/// @Name        SQL_SET_LOB_NULL
84315>>>>>>>/// @Description This command is used to set a LOB column to null. Often
84315>>>>>>>/// LOB columns should either contain data or be null. A "blank" LOB column
84315>>>>>>>/// often doesn't appear empty in other environments, so settings it back to
84315>>>>>>>/// null is best.
84315>>>>>>>///
84315>>>>>>>/// @Assumptions The field being used is a LOB field
84315>>>>>>>/// @Status      Public
84315>>>>>>>/// @Drivers     All
84315>>>>>>>/// @VersionNote Last Revised: 2014-07-10 by Aaron Gulack
84315>>>>>>>/// @See                 SQL_SET_LOB SQL_ADD_LOB_CHUNK SQL_GET_LOB SQL_GET_LOB_CHUNK SQL_LOB_TRUNCATE
84315>>>>>>>///
84315>>>>>>>/// @Syntax             SQL_SET_LOB_NULL    {FileName.FieldName}
84315>>>>>>>/// @Param              FileName                        The name of the file containing the LOB field
84315>>>>>>>/// @Param              FieldName                       The name of the specified LOB field
84315>>>>>>>///
84315>>>>>>>/// @Example
84315>>>>>>>////
84315>>>>>>>/// Clear Customer
84315>>>>>>>/// Move iID to Customer.ID
84315>>>>>>>/// Find Eq Customer by Index.1
84315>>>>>>>/// If (Found) Begin
84315>>>>>>>///    Reread Customer
84315>>>>>>>///        SQL_SET_LOB_NULL Customer.Comments
84315>>>>>>>///        Saverecord Customer
84315>>>>>>>///    Unlock
84315>>>>>>>/// End
84315>>>>>>>
84315>>>>>>>
84315>>>>>>>Procedure MertechInc_SQL_SET_LOB_NULL String sDriver Integer iFile Integer iField
84318>>>>>>>    Local String sLOB_Args
84318>>>>>>>
84318>>>>>>>    ZeroType tMertechLOB_Args to sLOB_Args
84319>>>>>>>    // First move the size of the structure to the Structure
84319>>>>>>>    Put tMertechLOB_Args_size to sLOB_Args at tMertechLOB_Args.cbSize
84320>>>>>>>    Put iField                to sLOB_Args at tMertechLOB_Args.nField
84321>>>>>>>
84321>>>>>>>    Call_Driver iFile sDriver Function CALLDRV_LOB_EX_SET_NULL CALLBACK 0 PASSING MertechInc_Blank MertechInc_Blank (addressof(sLOB_Args)) RESULT MertechInc_iRet
84326>>>>>>>End_Procedure // MertechInc_SQL_SET_LOB_NULL
84327>>>>>>>
84327>>>>>>>
84327>>>>>>>
