97680>>>>>    // When dropping columns on some SQL back-ends they doesn't reclaim the space taken up by the columns dropped. 
97680>>>>>    // For data types that are stored inline in the rows (int for example) it may even take up space on 
97680>>>>>    // the new rows added after the alter statement. to get around this you need to create a clustered 
97680>>>>>    // index on the table _or_ rebuild the clustered Index if it already has one. Rebuilding the index 
97680>>>>>    // can be done with a REBUILD command after modifying the table. But be warned this can be slow on very big tables.
97680>>>>>    //   ALTER TABLE MyTable
97680>>>>>    //       REBUILD
97680>>>>>    Function _SqlUtilRemoveTableColumnMSSQL String sTableName String sColumnName Returns Boolean
97682>>>>>        Boolean bOK  
